Kinshasa. Capital of the D.R.Congo. I have been dreaming about this city for two decades from my home town of Goma, 1500 km away. If it fascinated me to the point of moving there at the end of 2013, it is largely because of the way its 18 million inhabitants conceive life. In Kinshasa, problems, crises and disasters are nothing more than trials, and the struggle of the population is to find a " way of not surrendering " to a given trial. Thus, "Nzonzing" (Developed resourcefulness), "sapology" (the cult of dress and elegance), "mabanga" (payable dedications), "matolo" (made-up begging), etc. are, among many others, ingenious ways of not giving in to institutionalized chaos. 

The background of this film will be the realities of the first 3 years of this regime, which was born of the first peaceful alternation of the presidency of the republic. Presented as "civilized," much hope was placed in this noble gesture that saw for the first time ever a sitting president (M. Kabila) hand over the baton of leadership to an elected president (M. Tshisekedi). 

The story will be bolstered by the character’s poetry - both savory and zany - with which Lordi, Andria, Patrick and Enoch perpetually reinvent their "way of not surrendering". 

The narrative structure will have 3 layers. 
- The 1st layer is that of 4 stories. One story per main character. Narratives that are so close together that they will make and unmake each other and, ultimately, turn into one and the same story. A portrait of the group. 
- The 2nd is that of a “stop and go” cycle choregraphy. A choregraphy that will fix the group’s career, the journey of each member and the movement of bodies’s occupation of space. 
- The last one is that of a two-part journey : A physical ride made by the four characters every day to survive and an interior journey which brings them to the evidence long denied.

";s:22:"characters_description";s:2019:"Kinshasa is divided into two physical parts. The city center and the "cité". The city center is inhabited by the rich and the "cité" by the poor. "Cité" is short for the part that was called the "cité indigène" in colonial times.  Today it is home to 80 percent of the population. Living conditions are precarious and the infrastructure is either dilapidated or non-existent. It is in this atypical universe that Andria, Lordi, Enoch and Patrick live. Four young men, funny, creative and dynamic. They are the main characters of this film. 

They are a group of itinerant comedians who, in addition to their basic work, are constantly looking for a project that will immediately improve their living conditions. 10 years have passed since they created their group and since they tried several projects, hoping that each of them would be the saving project. The passage of time was not a problem for them as long as they could survive with the little they earned and as long as they did not turn to banditry like many young people from the "cité". Working as a itinerant comedian has always been a kind of outlet for them. Once disguised for the need of this work, Andria, Lordi, Enoch and Patrick adopt a character of “superhero”. Nothing affects them anymore. On the other hand, since they became parents everything has changed. They now have to take care of their wife and children. Hence the immediate obligation of results. It is from the moment they question their way of perceiving their work that the action of this film begins. 

They constitute a group that, like the "Beatles", does not prevent the personality of each of them from unfolding.

- An idealist, Enoch firmly believes in the advent of success that will change his life. 
- Leader, Lordi takes care of his image even if it means hiding his problems
- Mature, Patrick, father of three children, no longer has time to dream
- Disillusioned and entangled in a bunch of problems since birth, Andria uses the group to keep believing.";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:905:"The film NZONZING will use direct cinema techniques. The archives that will be used in it, will be initially introduced by the characters. The traditional media will be used to define the socio-political and economic realities of the place where the story takes place. 

The city of Kinshasa, which is a character in itself, will be filmed in such a way as to juxtapose its two physical parts. 

When edited, the images of the city centre will be dull and fast paced and those of the city will be vivid with a fast pace to allow for the easy deployment of each action. 

The sound will move beyond its status as an image confirmation element to come to the foreground in some scenes in a wide and fixed shot or in a sequence shot to define a cut. 

The music will be based on percussion. Its primary function will not be to accompany, highlight or propose emotions, it will play a part in itself. ";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:782:"About co-production. We received a proposal from the Canadian company QUIET REVOLUTION PRODUCTIONS inc. managed by Mr. Michael Dobbin. After analyzing the budget, this company has committed to contribute first with an amount of 15773 Euros. In the meantime, Mr. Michael Dobbin and his team are studying the possibilities of mobilizing other funds in Canada and in the USA. 

About distribution. QUIET REVOLUTION PRODUCTIONS inc. has made an offer from its subsidiary CAPITAL MOTION PICTURE GROUP to distribute the film alongside the company MAZIWA MAKUU FILMS of Ms. DJIA MAMBU. 

In addition, the project NZONZING will be presented at this year's DURBAN FILMMART. We are counting on this opportunity to attract other partners capable of helping us to materialize this project. ";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:2008:"I met them for the first time one afternoon in December 2018 while I was sitting on the terrace of a bar on the edge of Nyangwe Avenue (not far from the downtown). Andria, Lordi, Enoch and Patrick appeared in front of me and made me laugh with the jokes they were telling with application and frenzy. Impressed, I found myself obliged to give them some money before returning home praising their courage and genius. Their "way not to surrender" seemed to me to be a good answer to the unemployment that affects seventy percent of the Congolese. 

Curiously, I couldn't forget them. Their grim faces, their big brightly colored glasses, their laughter, the color of their beards, their false bloated bellies, their looks of superheroes ... Thinking about it, I began to wonder about the durability of their work and the nature of their mask in this city where appearance is an important social indicator. 

When I saw them again, I learned that they were a group of four itinerant comedians, that they lived in the "city" but worked exclusively in the downtown. This means that in order to work they have to cross fifteen kilometres each day, both on the outward and return journey. Their basic work consists of grimacing their faces and wearing grotesque outfits before criss-crossing the downtown, its surroundings, its bars and terraces to tell jokes and funny stories to people they meet. Sometimes these people give them a little money. That money is their gain.

Andria, Lordi, Enoch and Patrick develop projects, both ambitious and daring, and carry them out. If one project does not produce the desired results, they get together to find another. In the meantime, while waiting for a new project to be executed, they continue their core work as itinerant comedians. This basic work is the only one that so far has helped them to support themselves and the people for whom they are responsible. 

These four men alone crystallize the fears and vicissitudes of a youth abandoned to its sad fate.";s:14:"representation";s:2008:"The noun "Nzonzing" is used in Kinshasa slang to mean a sideline or extra activity, whether or not it is related to a person's main activity. No other word carries the subject of this film better than this timeless, anodyne noun.  

The Nzonzing film file we submit to you is not just a file, it is the emanation of a filmmaking device that took several months to clarify and a trivialized social phenomenon that, in our opinion, best defines the local society in which we live.

In 2018 Moimi Wezam released his first film entitled ZERO. This 66-minute documentary is in itself a sort of tribute to the late Papa Wemba (the only Congolese musical artist, to date, certified gold record in the United States). When on April 24, 2016, in Abidjan (Ivory Coast), Papa Wemba's unexpected death occurred, his dancer Benedicte Shutsha (who worked for him for fifteen years) was devastated. During his mourning, little by little, the idea of remixing the song ZERO of his late mentor became clear in his head. A perilous project whose objective was both to pay tribute to her former employer and to launch her singing career. The ups and downs of this adventure, Benedicte Shutsha's difficulties in finding her place as the heir to an African music icon and the fact that this project could help her mourn her loss served as the first hinges of the narrative for what became the film ZERO. 

A film with a steady pace whose first objective was to share with the audience the feeling of stagnation that plagued Benedicte during her mourning and the way she struggled to get rid of it. To this first choice was added a voice-over in the first person singular in which was concentrated an important emotional thickness. 

Moimi Wezam is proud of the result and of ZERO's journey. He believed in it, he wrote it and he mobilized the means to materialize it. With hindsight, he is convinced that if he had participated in the rewriting programs at the development stage and if he had succeeded in mobilizing more";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1620936639_1.jpg";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:6:"361050";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:5:"73843";s:12:"totalApplied";s:6:"287208";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:6:"287207";s:10:"budgetFile";s:0:"";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:11:"MOIMI WEZAM";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"3";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2023-06-23 14:39:33";s:5:"award";s:1:"1";}i:10;a:54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"111";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:2:"90";s:4:"name";s:43:"the tragedy of forced child labour in Benin";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"52";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:5:"21-59";s:7:"logline";s:52:"La tragédie du travail forcé des enfants au Bénin";s:15:"story_structure";s:1155:"Au Bénin, en dépit de toutes les dispositions qui ont été prises à travers les articles 13 de la constitution de 1990 du Bénin, l’article 166 du code du travail de 1998 et la loi de 2006 portant sur