";s:15:"story_structure";s:1978:"The female body has been many things and nothing through time. She has been bruised, battered, covered up, opened up, cut open. She has been trimmed, watered, pruned like a garden, she has been nourished like a fattened cow; she has flourished and has also withered away. 

This film will be a fascinating combination of archival materials showcasing the culture and practices of old as well as convincing interviews from scholars and emotional cinematography following the lives of our primary character; Lynda Okonkwo.

The beginning of the documentary will feature conceptualization; what is fat? What is beauty? Here, the scholars will take us on a journey through time from pre-colonial Nigeriansocieties and cultures through till modern times to give us a holistic understanding of African cultures surrounding beauty, fat, and the female body.

Next, we will follow the true-life story of our main character, Lyda Okonkwo, backing it up with the voices of selected women, to get their personal experiences of how cultural preferences of beauty have affected their life choices.
What will follow will be the reality of their life choices and how they have been living with these choices especially dealing with peer pressure, body shaming, and the evolving cultural perception of beauty. We will also hear from them, the limits they are going to readjust or reaffirm their bodies. Here, together with the personal experiences, interviews of industry professionals from clinical psychologists to gym instructors, will give us insights into body dysmorphic disorder, the age of digital beauty, the effects of cultural preference and peer pressures on women as it relates to their bodies.

The documentary will end in what I call, the Reclamation. Here, all the elements of the documentary will come together like a crescendo in a symphony. Our characters will talk about their future in relation to their bodies, self-esteem, and their understanding of happiness.
";s:22:"characters_description";s:721:"The documentary will be told through the eyes of Lynda Okonkwo. Lynda has a smile that can light up any room and it doesn’t take much to get a tear to drop from her eyes, perhaps that’s what makes her a terrific actor. She is a 120kg, 6ft, fair-skinned goddess, someone the film industry considers “too fat to fit into some roles”. 
For one in the spotlight, her body is constantly on display and opportunities to shine often evade her, and the little that fall on her laps are ladled with stereotype and body shaming. 
Underneath the wide smile and bubbling personality, is a girl who wishes people can see past the number on the scale and accept her for who she is; a brilliant actor with a beautiful smile.
";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1912:"The desired tone and visual representation of the subject matter are going to be tailored to resonate with and be reflective of the primary target audience; women. The story is character-driven and the subject matter will be explored through the life of our primary character. Interviews from learned fellows on different aspects of the subject matter will also feed into the narrative.

Each interview will be framed in a way that the locations become characters in the story. The locations will play an integral part in strengthening the narrative flow.
Beauty lighting will form the basis of the lighting design of this documentary. The lighting will tell a story; one of freedom and acceptance. The lighting will be flattery and complementary, concealing nothing. However, if a character being interviewed insists on anonymity, we will explore the use of silhouette and light shaping to keep the character hidden. We will go a step further in distorting the voice, not to a level where it will be inaudible but comfortable for the character to express herself.

The sound accompanying the story being told will be in layers. The documentary will open with a poem, glorifying the female body and the struggles it has endured over time. This poem will be accompanied by compelling images to lure the audience into the world they are about to experience. The emotional beats of the story will be accompanied by melancholy music to reel the audience in. Other explorative parts of the documentary will be complemented by soulful, alternative RnB.

The documentary will be made up of interviews, re-enactments, archival videos, and pictures much for the visual appeal of the audience. Because of the unavailability of certain footage, there will be a re-enactment of scenes by professional actors. The actor’s performance, however, will be as realistic as possible, in line with the flow of the story. 
