";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:4:"1400";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:1:"0";s:12:"totalApplied";s:4:"1400";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:4:"1400";s:10:"budgetFile";s:22:"2021/1617983682_1.docx";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:13:"Ernest Hilary";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"2";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-06-22 10:56:37";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:19;a:54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"140";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"160";s:4:"name";s:13:"Land of Women";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"90";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:200:"In a conservative village in south of Egypt, dominated by patriarchy, oppressive priests and secular tension, a group of Coptic girls refuses the traditional roles forced upon them, by forming all-fem";s:15:"story_structure";s:1933:"In a forgotten village, in the south of Egypt. An unforgiving sun, a parched earth, a high mortality rate among youngsters and a failed economy have left the village desolate. A place where women are rarely allowed to have an active role in public. A place known for sectarian turbulence between Copts and Muslims, in which Copts are killed and driven out of their homes for their faith, among attacks on churches. Disenfranchised Coptic girls rebel by forming an all-female street theater troupe. MONIKA, a girl with a jaundiced tomboyish voice dreams to be a famous singer. MAGDA, the young leader of the group dreams to study theater and be a theater director, in a place that lacks even the primary education. MARINA, a clueless girl suffers domestic violence and epileptic seizures. MERIEM, alongside her seven girls’ siblings, carries the shame of not having a brother in the family. HEIDI, dreams to be a ballet dancer but what does that mean to her illiterate parents? The girls resist the classical roles they are destined for. They role-play as women, boys, men and trees. They are at that age where they can be anything they imagine to be. Their chemistry, their camaraderie and their bond seduce us into a world of their own. They sing, dance and run around performing in the allies, chanting folk songs, contemplating their future and criticizing how their conservative culture dictates their behavior. Their actions confuse their families, challenging the villagers, priests and the camera. Their unawareness of their own limitations pushes the boundaries of theatre and film.
All of them are confronted by prejudice and a deeply misogynistic climate. Their activities come with a lot of risk-taking. The conservative priests ask the Coptic people not to participate or attend the girls’ performance. They are not that welcomed in the churches. They are harassed when performing in the allies with Muslim majority.";s:22:"characters_description";s:1933:"MONIKA
18-year-old MONICA, with a grand tattoo of the Virgin Mary on her right arm, stands out from the group with her tomboyish attitude and masculine voice. What makes it even harder is the misunderstanding she often encounters, the people who insult her, mock her voice and instantly judge him. Villagers call her (a dude) and (a freak) and she was subjected to bullying and mockery for years. Many ask her to make an operation to remedy her coarse voice. However, she loves to sing. She creates her own self-defense mechanism. A mixture of showing off, lying to herself, and lying to others.
MAGDA
21-year-old MAGDA is the troupe’s young leader with an aura of wisdom, a face full of acne, stubborn eyes and a charming smile. Magda’s conflict is her seeking of validation from her older and younger brothers. Magda’s dream is to study theater in the Theater Institute in Cairo.
MARINA
A 24-year-old MARINA holds sacred beliefs yet at the same time is needled by doubts and fears that she is unable to articulate. She does not trust herself. She does not see a future for herself. Her brother beats her regularly. She is observed at all times by everyone. She describes her condition as moving with chains around her feet. The weight of which, slows her down and wounds her.
MYRIAM
Myriam carries the shame of her family and her parents, having only a female progeny. It is a family of seven daughters. Girls mean a worse livelihood. Villagers prefer to have boys because they can depend on them in work and carrying on the family name and business.
HAIDI
HAIDY, is the troupe’s slender 17-year-old writer. She joins the troupe in spite of the reservation of her family and relatives, especially her priest uncle. Haidy practices theater every day. She dreams of becoming a ballet dancer and leaving her small village behind. She is playful and she has many secret love affairs through Facebook and social media. ";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:2000:"We aim to enter the bubble of these girls’ world, chasing the wildness and elusiveness of being young. Their lightheartedness contrasts starkly with the harsh reality of the future they are making plans for. In this coming-of-age story, we focus on those girls, who emanate strength, resilience, intelligence, courage, and love for each other. A hybrid of documentary aesthetic and unscripted narrative, depicting real people in an insular rural community, in which nonprofessional actors play versions of their real-life selves. That will allow us to explore the border between tragedy and freedom, control and submission, true and false, limitation and power of cinema. An interpenetration of fiction into reality and of reality into fiction. The camera holds in the edges of its frame the fear and restrictions those girls refuse to acknowledge. It interacts with the girls self-images and stories, allowing their journey, both visually and narratively, to play with the audience own perception.
We develop those characters through intimate close-ups that portray their internal struggles, self-deception, and pressure of their future, confusion and conflict of faith.
This story packed with personal drama follows the girls as they go about their turbulent daily lives, leaving plenty of space for livestreams, telephone conversations, intimate video diaries where they show what’s going on in their lives, from their own perspective, and share their thoughts about it. The sectarian violence events are also told through the mobile phone videos and livestreams.
That reality is intertwined with the girls’ dreams, stories and myths. That reveals not only their psychological state but also have a route in universal “spiritual traditions” in myths and religion. For instance, the girls walking on water, which has a resonance in Christianity and in Ancient Egyptian religion. Another example is Myriam, who always dreams of flying. We see her floating over her bed during her sleep.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1618057460_1.pdf";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:6:"438058";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:6:"112036";s:12:"totalApplied";s:5:"59500";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:6:"326022";s:10:"budgetFile";s:22:"2021/1618057732_1.xlsx";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:5:"Ayman";s:12:"project_role";s:8:"producer";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"2";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-06-25 15:03:51";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:20;a:54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"146";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"171";s:4:"name";s:14:"Miundombinu TV";s:6:"p_date";s:1:"9";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:4:"9-20";s:7:"logline";s:34:"'If you build it, they will come.'";s:15:"story_structure";s:1017:"