kipia East area, number only around 4,000. And only less than 5 people, all over the age of 70, can speak the ethnic group’s native language, Yakunte, fluently.

The Yaaku are believed to have migrated from Ethiopia to Kenya, where they settled in the Mukogodo forest, west of Mount Kenya, more than 100 years ago. They interacted with rendile and formed a tribe known as the Yaaku. The Yaaku, whose name means “hunting people,” kept bees and began trading with the Maasai, the country’s largest pastoral people. Eventually the Yaaku assimilated into Masai culture, adopting the Masai tongue over their own Cushitic language.

As the number of Yakunte speakers has dwindled, various efforts have been made to save the language. Yakunte speakers and a Dutch researcher wrote a Yakunte dictionary in 2004. Advocates of the people established the Yaaku People Association in 2003, dedicated to preserving its culture. Recently, according to a BBC report, a local school funded by the French Cultural Group is holding language classes twice a month for young Yaaku.

I have been part of this effort to preserve this language by featuring their culture and traditions  on a TV show that I produced called Foods Of Kenya. This however is not enough since it's only a feature.

I would love to produce a 60 min documentary, detailing this tribe's  livelihood, culture, songs  and tribe before it all gets extinct with the older generation. I believe that documenting this tribe in video will have more impact than even writing a dictionary with the languages,

The story structure will be following the life of a Yakunte speaking old man as he teaches children the tribe through, songs and dance, cultural beliefs, tradition and way of life.

