 standing refugee camps in Kakuma and Dadaab, where a total number of 430,000 asylum seekers call home.

For close to thirty years, asylum seekers from over fifteen countries in and beyond east Africa have called Kakuma their home. It is here that they have formed new communities, grown businesses, married, raised children and buried friends and family.

In our documentary Repatriation, we will follow Kenyan born and raised South Sudanese ‘refugee’ David Erjok. Unverified as a Kenyan citizen Erjok carries both Kenya and South Sudan heavy in his heart and like many, remains unsure what will his future holds.

The story picks up from Nairobi where Erjok currently undertakes his undergraduate studies at the Pan Africa Christian University. Just as he was growing accustomed to life in Nairobi, the coronavirus pandemic hit, limiting interactions with friends and family.  

Lonely and anxious, Erjok is keen to get back to Kakuma during the August break where he will discuss with his family their options, if at all.

Through this short but impactful cinematic film, Erjok will reveal the slow and painful erosion of asylum seeker’s rights worldwide.

Using Erjok’s poetry the film will conjure imagery of the countless lives of migrants lost at sea, children in detention centers, the growing demolitions in the West bank rendering many homeless, all the while questioning the right to a safe home.

Repatriation is a short documentary that will follow two key narrative threads: firstly, Erjok’s desire and journey for integration. 

Transporting the viewer from Nairobi to Kakuma, the second thread comes as a mix of beautiful stories from the host community, civil workers, expatriates and more whose lives will be affected by the closure of the camps. Through a number of micro-narratives, we will hear their idea of home and why integration is difficult.
