From his humble upbringing during the colonial period, to his first introduction to classical instrumentation and his music general band life experiences, Mzee Ngala’s journey to the discovery of Bango music is covered in detail.  

The film follows Mzee from his early education during the colonial times and gradually stretches into his introduction to music. It will integrate his family and professional life highlighting the struggles endured to discover the unique African tune in Bango music. 

This melodic documentary portrait builds up towards the climax of a RE-UNION concert full of his fans, where Mzee Ngala holds a Life Achievement performance alongside his former band mates and children.  
Outline
•	Early Life
Covers Mzee Ngala’s childhood in Mombasa born in October 1935. We deal with his education, family background, and his formative years. We learn the history of his hometown, Frere Town and Fort Jesus.
•	Introduction To Music
Mzee’s as he begins to discover his interest in music. It will cover his early employment before quitting several jobs and retirement at Railways Kenya to finally chase his dream of becoming a musician.
•	Band vs. Family Life
We learn of the names and history of all the bands Mzee transverses before he finally goes solo. We discover the challenges he underwent and how he invented the Bango music style. We re-connect him with his former bandmates and also get to know more of his love life as we build up to the reunion concert
•	Current state (Legacy)
Mzee Ngala’s current situation in his retirement home renovated by the county government. He is a loved and adored legend.";s:22:"characters_description";s:1728:"Mzee Ngala was born in 1933, in a small ward called Frere town, in Mombasa,. The ward, which used to be a depot for slaves for the colonial period, is where Mzee encountered his first music lessons and still lives up to date. 

Mzee Ngala performed in the past with famous groups such as the Hodi Boys and was also the founder and bandleader of the 1960s and 1970s famous group Bahari Boys. He started of playing the clarinet and later matured to be talented saxophonist. He quit a number of jobs to pursue his dream of becoming a musician. Alongside his friends he composed a song “Naitaka Bango” which gave the music genre its name.

He was faced with a series of band hopping and breaking during a time when reggae music was making its way into Africa. Like any other musician he was often engaged in band wrangles. However, he believed in the developing a new music genre for his people and decided to start a fresh band with his own children whom he had taught how to play different kinds of instruments over a period of time. His son, Jimmy Ngala, carries on his father’s legacy with a modernized style using his Tamaduni band.

Mzee Ngala is known for composing theme songs for local Television soap operas of the late 90s like “Kisulisuli” https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S7IDOyaXBqs.   Up to date, Mzee is always contracted to compose and perform songs for newly weds. 

At 85 years old Mzee Ngala, arguably the oldest Kenyan musician, is slowly aging like fine wine. His music is highly celebrated and listened to by millions of audiences regionally. He is often contracted to compose wedding songs for couples and even play in concerts & restaurants. He wishes to be re-united with is old memories
";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1937:"The film being a music & concert biopic, a full-length interview with Mzee Ngala will comprehensively give information of his past, present and possible future. Strategically structured questions will be used to lead the narrative to our preferred destination.

Many of Mzee Ngala’s photographs will be presented in concurrence with the time period being explained.  Archival footage from local T.V and ratio stations are vital with most of Mzee’s footage and sound recordings in custody of media stations. B-rolls, but not limited to establishing shots, will be taken of various historical locations at the coast where Mzee Ngala lived, worked and socialized.

Black and white dramatic re-enactments will backdrop Mzee’s narration of some major events that have already happened. Using creative face-hiding shots, we shall relive a bit of Mzee’s youth life seeing him learn how to play different instruments. The lighting used will have a mixture of both artificial and naturalistic approaches in order to craft a sense of harmony between his personal and professional life. 

Music tracks and songs composed by Mzee Ngala will be crucial to the storytelling. In a gradual and vibrant tempo, either a track or an instrument being played will occasionally enhance the story, giving it a melodic tone that brings nostalgic memories to the audience. 

All footage will be shot in full frame on a Black Magic Pocket Cinema 6k camera. A colorful glossy grade on the documentary will keep the audience in a happy celebratory mood. 

Interviews with musicians, influencers, relatives and even politicians will help the audience understand Mzee, both from a personal and professional level. Insights of bands from the 80s such as ‘The mushrooms’ interweaved with current bands e.g. ‘Sauti Sol’ and solo artists like ‘Nyota ndogo’ will highlight the greatness of Mzee Ngala and his influence to recent music trends.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1620140967_1.pdf";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:5:"42000";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:5:"10500";s:12:"totalApplied";s:4:"5000";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:5:"31500";s:10:"budgetFile";s:22:"2021/1620141162_1.xlsx";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:18:"Bill Jonnes Afwani";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"2";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-07-02 20:15:47";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:32;a:54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"258";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"500";s:4:"name";s:11:"The Syrians";s:6:"p_date";s:3:"100";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:196:"The crossed intimate portraits of three desire driven Syrians living in Lebanon at crucial human phases (birth, grown-up, death) composing a mosaic of life and troubling the concept of identity.  ";s:15:"story_structure";s:2017:"More than nine years after the protests began, Syria has known one of the largest exodus of its modern history, especially towards Lebanon, a country itself under high tension and sharing a particular history with neighboring Syria. 

Now, Syrians constitute one of the largest displaced populations in modern history (8 millions people inside the country and 5 millions outside). Despite having opened its borders Lebanon’s policy towards them has hardened since 2015, making renewals for temporary residence permits almost impossible. 

For instance, Lebanon does not recognize the “right of the soil”. Syrians living in Lebanon, in most cases for long years, are in a difficult situation: most of them are illegal residents, dozens of thousands of new- born children on Lebanese soil are stateless and if a Syrian dies in Lebanon, his/her body is often not accepted in cemeteries. What I essentially want is to capture the desires, goals, and dreams, the relentless humanity of those people enduring an inhumane situation, unwanted wherever they go.

For about a year and a half, I started conducting remote research from by home country of Tunisia, to draw out the first basis of the project. The film received development support from the IDFA Bertha Fund, the Arab Fund for Arts and Culture and the Beirut Film Station (Goethe Institute Lebanon), which allowed me to make several trips to Lebanon and feed my research. 

That’s how I met Fadia, Leena, and Abou Ala who started telling me about their lives. Thanks to these encounters, I was able to conceive a first narrative framework for my project and a provisional structure.

The film will be composed of these portraits at different moments of life, and put together, they will create a storyline which will go from pregnancy to exile and emancipation. These characters make up the pieces of a much more complex puzzle. They represent the multiplicity of humanity, at a time when displaced populations are often considered as statistics.";s:22:"characters_description";s:630:"Leena is 6 months pregnant and lives in a tower in the north of Tripoli, Lebanon, along with a dozen other Syrian families ; Abou Ala lives in an informal settlements in the Bekaa Valley region, he is obsessed with the fact to bury his elderly father with dignity ; Fadia dreams of immigrating to Canada where she will be able to start hormonal treatment to become a woman.

The three of them have fled war-torn Syria and found refuge in Lebanon. Through their portraits emerge the fractures and paradoxes of a region under high tension as each one of them is struggling to achieve a goal and realize a dream in a hostile exile.";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1640:"The film is to be shot mostly in Beirut, but also in the coastal cities of Tyr (south of the country) and Tripoli (in the north) in order to properly cover the nationwide humanitarian tragedy that is happening there. Lebanon has become the equivalent of an open-air camp now that the number of Syrians refugees on its soil is almost reaching 1.5 million people. Scattered across the country these men an women live in “informal settlements” and “collective shelters” but also in disused and abandoned buildings, in huts in the middle of fields or in garages and deposits.

Regarding my filmmaking approach, I intend to do most of the shots with handheld camera. The different portraits will also be part of a larger mosaic of people and families living in different situations and different locations in Lebanon. During editing, long shots will punctuate the film, as a way of reporting on their marginal status. Shots that will cross the line of conventional editing, as if to retain as many gestures, sensations and emotions as possible.

How can one be filming when he/she is at the heart of one of the most important events in terms of international issues?
This represents to me a visceral question, since my body is being involved in the process as a filming and testifying tool. This singular situation calls for a cinematographic reflection and invention. My documentary will not be informative nor didactic, but rather intimate, close to the people I will film. It will pay attention to what surrounds them - Lebanon as a territory and as a society. It focuses on deconstructing rather than constructing a discourse.
";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1620642137_1.png";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:6:"172438";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:6:"123000";s:12:"totalApplied";s:5:"50000";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:5:"49438";s:10:"budgetFile";s:21:"2021/1620730363_1.xls";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:7:"ismaël";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"2";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-06-22 10:38:42";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:33;a:54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"262";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"519";s:4:"name";s:32:"Untitled 'Umra Omar' Documentary";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"90";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:202:"At a moment of historical change in Kenya’s ancient Lamu archipelago, a lion-hearted mother of two puts her organisation and family-life in jeopardy to run for Governor & fix a broken public system.  ";s:15:"story_structure";s:2016:"Umra Omar was raised in Lamu by her grandmother before studying and working in the US as a psychologist. She returned home in 2014 just as Lamu was attacked by Al Shabab fighters, leaving dispensaries & schools in the area deserted. That’s when Umra founded Safari Doctors to provide medical services to the communities cut-off by the conflict. 

After 6 years growing the organization beyond expectations, the Lamu streets are overflowing with trash while the state-run medical facilities have deteriorated further, often empty of personnel, medical supplies & even running water. Umra’s frustration with a corrupt local government has finally reached breaking point, and her decision to run for Governor (the highest seat of power) in the upcoming elections is already disrupting the male-dominated political order, who’ve never had to contend with a female candidate so vocal about their failing leadership.  

Situated on Kenya’s northern coastal border, Lamu is famous for its exquisite Swahili architecture, 14th Century old town & untouched tropical islands. Isolated & neglected since independence, Lamu is the third poorest county in Kenya. But change is imminent with a $25B infrastructure project featuring a China-funded mega-port, industrial city, coal power plant and oil pipeline. This has triggered a scramble for land by outside businessmen, as tensions rise with the locals whose fisheries and mangrove forests are being destroyed, along with a growing Kenyan and US military presence trying to gain control over lawless southern Somalia.

It is amongst this geo-political quagmire that 37-year-old Umra is transitioning from humanitarian hero to a bare-knuckled political organizer. With no political experience or corporate backing, amidst a growing onslaught of misogynistic vitriol, this film is a close-and-intimate chronicle of Umra’s decision to dance with the devil, revealing the huge personal costs to her and her family as she enters the scrappy arena of Kenyan politics.";s:22:"characters_description";s:2022:"Umra Omar, the eldest of 3 sisters, grew up barefoot in the remote Pate Island village of Tchundwa, raised by her grandmother, a matriarch who had 8 husbands and 18 children.  Reunited with her parents in Nairobi after they finished their studies, Umra was awarded a high-school scholarship at Atlantic College in Wales before studying neuroscience & psychology at Oberlin College in USA. After her first placements in Washington DC and New York City, she returned to Kenya in 2014 for a job with Open Society Foundation, before the Al Shabaab attacks in Lamu compelled her to start Safari Doctors.

Umra’s father, Omar Bwana is an anomaly amongst Swahili men for educating his three daughters at an ivy-league level. As a young man, his work in preserving Swahili culture impressed the paleoanthropologist Richard Leakey, and together they founded Lamu Museum, excavating the many ancient Swahili ruins dotted around the archipelago. Omar was a prolific political organiser in the 1950’s, forming the Shungwaya Party to begin agitating for Kenya’s independence. In 1972 he was selected by President Moi as a nominated Member of Parliament before becoming chairman of National Museums of Kenya. Umra’s biggest cheerleader, he has been quietly pulling strings behind the scenes & calling upon his political contacts to open their doors to his daughter.

Other characters in the film include Umra’s 2 children Azza & Bwana. Umra’s chief-of-staff Ismael Bwana & her campaign manager Sande Oyolo, who is closely aligned with William Ruto, the current Vice-President of Kenya, and favourite to win the presidency in 2022.

Umra’s mother and two sisters are also of interest. Since Umra’s announcement to run, they are asked for money everywhere they go, and the prices for a boat-taxi, motorbike or even a meal at a restaurant have now doubled. Already uncomfortable with this disruption to their lives, they are not yet agreeable to be in the film, but we hope this will change as the campaign progresses";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:2019:"UMRA is an intimate and personal feature-length documentary following the life of a political candidate over 18 months leading to election day.  We will mix verite scenes & informal interviews filmed with deeply saturated colours and a sharp, cinematic visual approach in the style of an international noir spy-thriller, set amongst the enchanting fishing-village of Lamu.

Iconic for it’s fusion of cultures over thousands of years of Indian Ocean trade between Africa, Arabia, Europe, India and China, Lamu’s coral fortresses hold ancient secrets that pass with the wispy perfume of fully-veiled women in black buibuis. Donkeys bray throughout the day as traders dust away sand from their stalls of tropical fruit & spices. The Imam’s 5 daily calls to prayer resonate through the narrow cobbled streets & an influx of men in white kanzus enter and exit the many mosques for their time with Allah, a refreshing purity amongst the otherwise stifling heat.

The relaxed observational scenes of Umra and her family at home will contrast the intense pressure and chaos of the political campaign & rallies. We will play visually with a dual consciousness which Umra describes as a mental separation of her real life self (known only to her friends and family) from her public ‘poster’ persona (alone and isolated, where people demand everything from her like a walking ATM).  We also want to visually explore Umra’s background in neuro-science, psychology and public-health, and her love of chess, to articulate a deeply cerebral awareness of human nature, and how that translates into her political strategy.

Musically the film will feature an original score co-composed by director Maia (a prolific Kenyan musician) together with local swahili musicians who carry the richness of Taarab music, fusing middle-eastern scales with stringed orchestras and deep african drum syncopation.  The score will also be electronic, gritty and industrial at times, to build and release the story’s tension & drama.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:132:"Filming has continued in May and June, several more foundational scenes have been captured.  Currently concentrating of fundraising.";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:2008:"UMRA is a story that needs to be told now, and needs to be told well - with a passion and tenacity that mirrors the protagonist. Our first 2 features (The Letter, 2019 and How to Build a Library, in production) also feature unbelievably strong women who spoke to us so deeply that we kept at it for years because these are the stories the world needs to see.

Our third feature, UMRA is our most ambitious and risky project yet: with a short time-frame, in a location where logistics are expensive, security is volatile, and a protagonist who is ruffling some very powerful feathers. Since November 2020, we’ve travelled to Lamu 3 times and managed to film and cut a fundraising trailer without any financial support, while simultaneously releasing and producing our first 2 films.

Having captured several key scenes of the foundational stages of the campaign, our primary goal has been to form a deep relationship with Umra built on trust, honesty and mutual respect.  Having known Umra and her sisters since 2015, we were able to jump straight into filming with her and her kids, staying at her place to immerse ourselves into her life and enjoy many long conversations into the night to understand each other better and discuss the overwhelming need for a political revolution in Kenya. This is the foundation on which the next 18 months of filming rests, together with our cultural awareness, speaking the language and our own Swahili-roots (Maia’s father’s family lineage connects back to Lamu sultan in the 1800’s, Umra’s father even has a book about the life of Maia’s Great-Grandfather).

Lamu is a heavily walled city, insular and encrypted to most outsiders.  Umra and her family are unique in their openness to a film crew, and between the strength of our relationship, her love of the camera and a strong pride to showcase her culture and homeland, this film will provide an insight into swahili culture, family-life and local Kenyan politics that few films have ever achieved.";s:14:"representation";s:1943:"As we see time & again, Kenyan superheroes like Umra are ultimately powerless in a broken system, and the film will highlight the immense price paid by those who try to change it. A strong dramatic engine is inherent in Umra’s mission, along with a clear ending. The 2 main narrative challenges we anticipate are (1) accessing her political opponents, and (2) capturing the protagonist’s more ruthless side which may contradict her clean public image. By employing a good local fixer we can overcome the 1st & the 2nd will be solved by remaining independent, which Umra understands is a vital ingredient to making the story realistic & compelling. Umra cannot survive the journey unscathed, and she is open & honest about us filming the risks & moral compromises she must make to win.

So far we’ve shot everything ourselves (Maia: sound / Chris: camera). On our 3rd, current trip in Lamu we’ve brought a DoP from Nairobi to build familiarity with the subjects, as we prepare to give birth to our first child in August 2021. A grant from DOCA would allow us to ensure the DoP & fixer can continue capturing the unfolding events from July to October. We then intend to rent a house in Lamu long-term & make a second base to continue filming the campaign through to August 2022. 

The film will be shot in 4K with cine prime lenses to achieve a cinematic vitality.  We’ve been inspired by films like “Knock Down The House”, “War Room” as well as Samaher Alqadi’s feminist inditement of the arab spring “As I Want”, and Sam Soko’s “Softie” which lay bare the flawed Kenyan political process.  We want to push the documentary genre by emulating the framing, suspenseful editing, music and aerial cinematography from film-noirs like “Chinatown” and spy-thrillers such as “The Girl With the Dragon Tattoo” & “Bourne Identity'' which we feel can help elevate the film’s aesthetic and commercial appeal.
