Ghana has a huge deposit of bauxite discovered in three locations namely, Awaso – which has been under severe mining in the past 76 years, Nyanahin – which has been given out last year to be mined and the popular Atewa Forest – which has been used as an exchange for 2 billion dollars from the Chinese Synohydro Company. The Atewa Forest has been earmarked for a National Park where experts say its ecological benefits over a longer period far outweighs the benefits of mining bauxite in the forest. The forest is Ghana’s remaining closed forest covering a total of 263 square kilometers.
 
In 2017 the Government of Ghana exchanged the forest for a 2 billion Chinese facility which has seen fierce resistance from NGOs, Community folks and CSOs. In 2019 the Chinese miners have created access routes in the Atewa forest. 

This story investigates how bauxite mining will destroy the fine ecosystem and contaminate the source of drinking water for over 6 million Ghanaians. It will also investigate as a prelude to the main documentary the projects that are supposed to be done under the arrangement and how far they have come up. It will require travelling to all the project sites and seeing at first-hand what they look like. The investigations will also extend to how community folks in Awaso bauxite mining community live in poverty and have seen no development for the past 77 years. 
