Nicole was born and raised in the slum area of Kibagare, Nairobi. She immediately was born into being a likely candidate of early pregnancies. 37% of girls between the ages of 15-22 years in two Nairobi slums have had at least one unwanted pregnancy. 	 
Nicole’s mother, Susan, gave birth to her first born, Nicole, at the age of 16. Susan too was born and raised in the slums of Kibagare. When she realized that she was pregnant, she moved in with her then boyfriend and that was how her family began. Susan’s  neighbor is her mother.  
Nicole’s story cuts across three generations of Matriarchs who have lived and grown up in poverty. 
Nicole’s grandmother, Nicole’s mother and then Nicole. They all have their lives orbiting around Kibagare Slums.  A bill to introduce sex education in Schools in Kenya was tabled in parliament. However this was met with strong opposition from religious leadership. With no sexual reproductive health information, , this then means that a girl, born into poverty, in the slums of Nairobi, will most likely get pregnant as a teenager and then drop out of school. She will then live her life, tethered to the slum.  This vicious cycle is the machinery that eventually leads to a surge of teenage pregnancies.  
 We will explore:  
1.	Nicole’s Family Background 
2.	Her Environment growing up and the influences around her 
3.	Her teen pregnancy journey 
4.	Poverty as a link to early pregnancy and broken families  
5.	Nicole’s journey back to school after spending a lot of time away  
6. Linkage between Nicole's story and her peers.
