ace in their quest to be the best at their respective sporting codes. Each episode will focus on a specific topic and two sports stars";s:22:"characters_description";s:1889:"EPISODE ONE – UMBHOXO

This episode will focus on rugby and look at Khaya Malotana and Makazole Mapimpi. Malotana grew up in Jojweni Village in Lady Free about 20 kilometres from Queenstown in the Eastern Cape. He became the first Black African to play for the Springboks in 1999 and went on to become a respected television commentator and presenter. He has also coached numerous schools, club and university teams.

Mapimpi grew up in Tsholomnqa, a small rural village near Mdantsane in the Eastern Cape. His rugby career did not follow the typical route of most of his peers – strong school then provincial contract and finally the national team. Instead, he played amateur club rugby until he was 24 years old and was discovered by the now defunct Border Rugby Union after his club won a local tournament. He went on to play 14 matches for the Springboks and became the first South African player to ever score a try in the Rugby World Cup Final.

This episode will look at the divisive history of rugby in South Africa, and how the sport was popular in the Black communities. There will be an archival look at some of the players who were denied the opportunity to play for the national team prior to 1994. The episode will then move to Lady Free to look at where Malotana grew up, speaking to his family and friends. There will also be an interview with the Headmaster of Queens’ College, where Malotana played until his matric year. 

Another insert will be filmed in Tsholomnqa, with Mapimpi’s family and former teammates. There will be shots showing the fields where the local village rugby tournaments are held and juxtapose those against the lush stadiums where provincial rugby is played in South Africa. 

Both sportsmen will be asked about the challenges they faced growing up, their role models, how growing up in rural areas shaped their careers, etc.

";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:918:"The documentary, Small Villages Big Dreams, utilises the narrative documentary technique. The athletes’ stories are illuminated through the biographical approach, telling the stories with a beginning, middle and end. Since the athletes are alive, the “end” will look at their current endeavours and future plans. 

Narration is provided by a narrator using a third person, talking over picture montages and video clips to inform the viewer on the athletes’ journeys. The narrator acts as an observer, conveying the facts of the athletes’ lives and career experiences. 

The athletes’ interview clips act as first-person point of view throughout the film, informing and entertaining the viewer first-hand about their life and career highlights. Other characters, including family members, teammates and coaches, are also interviewed and give their own opinions on key moments in the athletes’ lives.
