Her incredible work is through Facebook, bringing abuses to light and appealing for help. The cases have a common thread, violence! A mother escaping an abusive husband, a rape victim in a police station… 

Her frequent Facebook postings are an indication of the rise in physical and sexual violence, she uses social media to defend and fight for victim’s rights and to link people who need help and those who can help.

The documentary will adopt a cinema verité style and will document Njeri as she goes about rescuing victims using Facebook to involve the general public in her efforts, it will follow the stories of 6 women for a period of 6 months from the point of rescue, to the unknown and uncertain future. 

By covering Njeri’s everyday life, we see what keeps her going in the face of her successes, failures and lack of concerted government support, the cost that she and her family has to bear to keep her rescue operations going, plus the sacrifices she has had to make in order to create a future for the victims.

Through her, we shall get access to supportive law enforcement officers, organisations and individuals who assist in legal matters and financially to safeguard Njeri’s campaign.
The documentary will cover all facets that combine together to bring to light the plight of gender-based violence victims, the scope is on the social, legal, economic and political aspects that have contributed to an increase especially during lockdown due to Covid-19 

