The film will endeavour to keep true to the colours and sound that are the environment of Njeri's life.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1620953803_1.jpg";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:5:"42110";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:1:"0";s:12:"totalApplied";s:1:"0";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:5:"42110";s:10:"budgetFile";s:22:"2021/1620954260_1.xlsx";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:14:"Mwaniki Njache";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"2";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-06-25 15:16:21";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:62;a:54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"397";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"742";s:4:"name";s:20:"Adipala to the World";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"90";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:200:"What does everyone want? What has every successful person, or nation had? A chance to succeed. This is the story of an Ugandan scientist and visionary on a lifelong quest to give himself and his under";s:15:"story_structure";s:1271:"Professor Ekwamu Adipala is considered Uganda’s top crop scientist and a key driver of Africa’s green revolution; a tireless campaigner to support African tertiary education through networking, to date, 183 universities in 38 African countries. The film is his journey, in his own words, as the relentless, hard and beautiful quest to rebuild Africa's universities and give his continent a fighting chance. A journey fraught with brutal conflict, sacrifice and loss, held on course by love, resilience and African women.

Using unique personal access to the subject and his family and rare archive material of post independent Uganda and beyond, the film is both a poignant love letter to the Ugandan education system and a reflection on the experiences that shaped Prof as a person. It is a deeply intimate meditation on how to build a prosperous, unified Africa envisioned under Pan-Africanism and the African Renaissance, one small seed at a time. This is the story of African Higher Education and the urgent need to educate the world's fastest growing youth population before it is too late. Before the chance to harness the opportunities presented by the digital revolution for the world’s fastest growing economies is lost to others more skilled. 

";s:22:"characters_description";s:1878:"In 2021, Professor Adipala Ekwamu is retiring as a university professor, distinguished researcher, recipient of an honorary doctorate from University of Gweiza (Sudan) and having assisted more than 2500 students with scholarships to pursue studies in crop sciences. It’s a very different world from his upbringing as a herdboy in Olyanai, Uganda. Yet the values taught by his adoptive grandmother Ada Akello - now 100 years old - and the hard-won formal schooling paid for by the village women including the village witch doctor, are the foundation for a 40 year academic career contribution to realising a Green Revolution in Uganda and establishing an illustrious pan-Africa network for crop scientists.

The oldest of 13 children and the only sibling to receive a formal education, Adipala’s journey is from a tiny arid village through the hallowed halls of Uganda’s top schools and prestigious Makerere University to a doctorate obtained in the USA against the backdrop of Uganda’s torrid and brutal post-independence history and the collapse of education under Idi Amin and later the deplorable Joseph Kony and his Lord’s Resistance Army. 

Upon his return from the USA in 1992, Adipala sets about planting the seeds for a revitalised agricultural science revolution in Uganda that grows into a network of 10 universities across five African countries by 2004 and is set for even greater successes when the unthinkable happens: his wife is diagnosed with throat cancer. In the painful years after her passing, he throws himself into his work and expands the Regional Universities Forum for Capacity Building in Agriculture (RUFORUM) to 114 partner universities across 38 African countries. 

“Every life journey is an unfinished journey. And when you or I or anyone else is gone, there will be others preparing to take our places and carry on our work”.";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1821:"This feature documentary utilises an observational and participatory approach as the camera follows the protagonist Prof Adipala: he always invites the camera and viewer into his story with a friendly “You are welcome, please come…”. This irascible story-teller, great intellectual yet down-to-earth childhood mango-thief is is the heart of the film, creating a mood of bittersweet nostalgia but with an understanding that the past is not a fairy tale idyll. Although Prof grew up in the most unstable decades of Uganda’s recent history, often brutal and violent, his vision for the growth that comes from that is infused with connection to the ideal of a pan-African renaissance, grown through networking, a celebration of diversity and commitment. 
  
The film gives us access to a mostly unseen world. With a powerful central protagonist – a natural orator - it is a character-driven story that digs deep into universal themes. Dreams, struggles, family, love and loss. An uncertain future. The story of the underdog. Our protagonist trusts the camera and is open, honest and emotional, giving us intimate access to a colourful, brutal, hopeful and brilliant life story. The personal narrative carries with it the story of a continent and it’s people. Africa’s pain and resilience through a violent past, struggles for independence and the lasting wounds (and benefits) of colonialism. We experience a new perspective on Africa’s youth, it’s tertiary institutions and the race to prepare those youth for the rapid growth and opportunity presented by the continent as the next emerging global economy. Will our protagonsit’s lifelong struggle for a Pan African youth that are skilled, prosperous and proud of their Africaness, be able to carry his baton forward? A whole continent depends on it. ";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:490:"As part of our preparation for the Durban FilmMart we are receiving mentorship regarding the narrative structure of the film and look forward to sharing the project in July. 

A shoot in Uganda is looking possible for July that will be funded through another project but we will need to schedule one more shoot in November in Benin when Prof Adipala retires - this will be a key sequence in the film. 

We continue to work on the rough cut, applying for funds and seeking co-producers. ";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:1376:"My motivation for telling the story is to reveal to a global audience, a world seldom seen. A brilliant, exciting and brutal world that challenges traditional narratives of Africa as a broken, hopeless place. A world of young people fighting for their future and the right to their own continent. I have made 58 short films for Professor Adipala and the RUFORUM Network since 2013. I’ve visited 28 African countries am deeply immersed in the current conversation about African Higher Education and it’s challenges and critical role in African Development. 
I have come to know Prof Adipala very well. And I believe I have been given rare access to his personal and emotional life. I’ve learned about the role of capacity building for young scientists and their institutions on a continent with the lowest scientific output. I’ve seen firsthand the impact of young scientists and their innovative technologies for their communities. Many times lifting whole communities out of poverty. I have seen the potential of the ‘new African scientist’ and I want to amplify that story so that the dominant narrative of Africa is challenged. 
