 and foremost, the richest of cultures, talents and potentials. However, as every other slum dwelling, competition for a better livelihood coupled up with negative societal vices such as drug abuse, Kibera has produced several individuals and gangs that have terrorised the city in general. With low employment rates, young people have sought refuge in such vices and have in turn lost their freedom and lives in many cases. However, some have, voluntarily or otherwise, turned their lives around and sought better and legal ways to earn their livelihoods. An example of this is a group of reformed criminals who have formed a self help group, "Mwamko Kwa Vijana" that collects trash and cleans a local popular market, Toi Market, for a fee paid by the market sellers. As a group of around 15 former criminals, their main agenda is to work together as a group earning a legal income and not backsliding to crime, as well as trying to persuade peers in the night life to do the same. I met this group in 2020 and filmed their story (as the DOP) for a documentary by China Global Television Network(CGTN). The documentary is about the hidden talents, potentials and positive stories of Kibera, this groups story being a small part of a greater narrative. Moved by their story of rebuilding their lives and enticed by the idea of how visually exciting a more in depth film about them would be, I pick them as my pitch for the grant.";s:22:"characters_description";s:1063:"The narrative will be carried by 3 characters, Isaiah, Biko and Steven.
