Senegal, the small archipelago is known for its rich musical culture, having as its biggest ambassador the worldwide
recognized Cesária Évora.
For Patricia, music represents a small haven from her reality and a chance to become famous and change her life. She
prepares herself to compete in the second season of a local singing completion tv series while she takes care of her
newborn baby and her older son that, like her, has inherited a degenerative blindness. The 5-year-old child has also
abruptly stopped talking, increasingly showing signs of autism.
And who will cook? has been a constant question in both her and her mother’s lives by the men who, after getting
them pregnant, abandoned them for being blind.
Patricia creates her own place in society questioning matters of gender, equality and disability while attempting to
make her dream come true.";s:22:"characters_description";s:1976:"MAIN CHARACTERS
PATRICIA MAIA
Only 23 years old, Patricia is the mother of a 3-year-old boy and has recentlygraduated high school in Achada São Filipe. She is completely blind on her left eyeand almost completely on her right one.
Patricia lives in São Pedro’s neighborhood, Praia, Cape Verde. She has known rejection from a very young age: first from her father who abandoned her when she was still a baby, then from her primary school teacher, the father of her son, etc.
Even so, she managed to study through ADEVIC, she speaks Creole and Portuguese and some French and English.
Patricia dreams of being a singer. She doesn’t want to be dependent on state funds forever, and wishes to be economically independent so she can have her own house
and raise her son.
She has recently started dating someone new, who appears to be very supportive of her condition and her dreams. She is torn between wanting to be the best mother
she can be to Kenny and actually enjoying being young and pursuing her dreams freely. She attempts to do both.
She is very concerned about her son’s health and wants to try and prevent him from going blind and understand why he has stopped talking. She is the main character and the narrative evolves around her.
TITIA
Titia, Patricia’s mother is completely blind. She was also abandoned by the two fathers of her daughters. She works as Patricia’s mentor and gives us context from her birth and how she was raised.
She lives with her two daughters and her grandson, Kenny.
Titia is very active and is always busy at ADEVIC’s workshops, batuku rehearsals and doing cakes and sweets that she then sells.
KENNY
Patricia’s son, Kenny, is 4 years old and already shows the same symptoms – losing his sight as time goes by. He as also stopped talking recently, which is an alarming sign of regression. He does not have any relationship with his
father and Patricia is the one who raises him with the help of her mother. ";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1263:"“And who will cook?” will be a character documentary and will be shot mainly in cinema verité style. We will follow
Patricia while she prepares herself for “Voice One”, a local TV competition series, which will be the leading thread of
the documentary.
Sound will be immensely important in this documentary because it is the sense that allows Patricia to “see”, so it will
have to be our primary sense to be activated. If there’s a fly in the room we’ll need to hear it before we see it.
Music will also be a fundamental element throughout the film. Not only does it represent a dream for Patricia but it
also illustrates Cape Verde. Therefor it will be present in Patricia’s life in multiple ways – her humming songs, her
rehearsing for the competition, on the radio at her house, on her batuku rehearsals with other blind women and also
as a transition between sequences.
Patricia, like her mother and her older son, has been losing her sight gradually.
In “And who will cook?”, we’ll explore that concept visually through the focus. We’ll begin the film focusing exclusively
in Patricia and her family, having everything else unfocused. As the documentary progresses we’ll increasingly start
focusing on everything.
";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1621271298_1.pdf";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:6:"396000";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:4:"5000";s:12:"totalApplied";s:5:"83500";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:6:"391000";s:10:"budgetFile";s:22:"2021/1621273207_1.xlsx";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:12:"Pedro Soulé";s:12:"project_role";s:8:"producer";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"2";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-07-02 20:20:46";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:67;a:54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"408";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"859";s:4:"name";s:13:"Torch Bearers";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"90";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:4:"9-20";s:7:"logline";s:155:"Stories about men and women who took the leap of faith when an African person was only fit for servitude, they set up a stage where many can thrive today. ";s:15:"story_structure";s:1944:"IT ALWAYS SEEMS IMPOSSIBLE UNTIL IT’S DONE, Nelson Mandela. 
They took the first step of bravery against all odds.  They didn’t entertain the colour of their skin or their gender. They lived in a time when being black was almost a curse, yet they were able to rise above that.  They didn’t do it for themselves but for their fellow men who were despised and degraded in every possible way. They set up a stage and today many others can follow in their footsteps. 
These are stories of triumph.  Today South African women can enjoy their freedom and be able openly speak about the challenges they face but before all this, Bertha Mkhize had to be brave. She had to stand up for every woman who came before her and those who came after her. Like Bertha KE Masinga also did something remarkable when he walked into a white only SABC building in Durban and became the first black radio presenter. For the first time black people could listen to their own language and be proud. Another brave man was Simon Mkhize who ran the comrade marathon six times unofficially before he was to be recognised. He loved to run the 80 km marathon but he was black and it took longer for him to receive a green card.  Another brave woman who went against the odds, paving the way for others is Sibusisiwe Violet Makhanya. She became the first black social worker in South Africa.
These documentaries will give us a glimpse of the historical foundations to different disciplines. We shall learn about the participation of black people in different fields in the era where black people were refused participation. These documentaries will open the doors to the world and history of broadcast, sports, literature, business and social services in South Africa. This was the time when one needed to be brave in order to achieve their aspirations. These stories will be intertwined with today’s world in order to understand how we arrived where we are today. ";s:22:"characters_description";s:1386:"BERTHA MKHIZE was born in Embo in 1889 but shortly after, she lost her father. She received her  education at  Inanda Seminary and Ohlange. These are schools where Bertha received her education before she started teaching. She taught until she was thirty years and called it quits in order to pursue her business passion.  SIMON MKHIZE was born in 1942 in Howick. He grew up in a farm in Underberg . He then moved to Pietermaritzburg where he started running at the age of 28.  BUSISIWE MAKHANYA grew up in Mbumbulu in KZN and like all other village girls she collected water from the river and did all other chores that were expected of her. When she was nine years old she attended the Inanda Seminary School for girls. In 1927 she earned a scholarship to study in the US. MAGEMA MAGWAZA was born around 1840 in Zululand to the Ngcobo clan. Magena was also a messenger for Colenso, sending messages to King Cetshwayo. This gave him an exposure to the Zulu royal family and he developed a relationship with the King, who he described as “good, kind and loved by his people”. KE MASINGA was born in 1904 in Mzumbe. The story of KE gives us an opportunity to explore the history of radio in South Africa. The radio in South Africa started in the 30’s from humble beginnings as a platform for the wartime report service, propagating certain ideals and values from a central source. ";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:745:"This will be a five part series but each episode will be treated with the similar style. The films will invite experts and those who were close to the characters to give commentary on their lives. Archives will be used to attest to the character’s lives. For those who don’t have much archives in terms of photos, audio and visuals, re-enactment will be used to portray their lives. The interviewees will be filmed in their natural environment, with the soft background and focusing on the subject. The past will be compare with the present, e.g KE Masinga presenting during his time and the presenters today at Ukhozi FM. We will use sappier colours when reflecting on the past and bring back the colour when referring to the presence. 

