";s:15:"story_structure";s:788:"SYNOPSIS:
Ubungoma is a documentary, which seeks to educate audiences on the practice of Ubungoma, with an added emphasis on the reconnection of Africans to our identity and ancestry. The inspiration of the documentary bore from my own experiences with my former partner's journey as iSangoma/Traditional Healer & my curiosity this subject matter  & how little is known about it particularly in a younger demographic. We aim to explore the relationship between spirituality and modernization, religion & demonstrating how the world co-exist as opposed to collide. 

GENRE:
Participatory Documentary

TARGET MARKET:
This subject matter has such a wide range of appeal across a broad spectrum of LSM’s and ages groups starting from the young and in school right up to the elderly
";s:22:"characters_description";s:231:"We introduce the following interviewees: Gogo Esme, Gogo Malepena, Gogo Muhlavasi Emma Kejoe & Gobelas’ from Mpande’s representing ama Ndau and Mnguni who detail their journeys as well as taking through their various practices.";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1970:"LOGLINE:
A deep dive into the world of African shamanism.

ACT 1 – UBUNGOMA
The first act serves as the foundation of our subject matter, Ubungoma. We want to evoke emotion from the viewer straight out the gate. The establishing shot of the Sangoma dancing in this scenic view. Focusing not just on the movements but the emotion of the dancer this will be highlighted by using close up shots tightly cropped right alongside wide angles of the sunrise, which will set the scene

ACT 2:   THONGO LAM
This part focuses on educating the viewer on various types of spirits and the way they manifest themselves within their host. Showing the various distinctions and their importance showing how multifaceted it is 

ACT 3:  INKATHAZO
Here we begin to explore the legal ramifications associated with Ubungoma. We dive straight into our first interviewee, the esteemed Makhosi Dhlamini. We want to keep this footage as raw and unrehearsed as possible. Many handheld shots following her around her practice just to give it an intimate feel. Our interviews will be shot with two cameras, our main establishing shot and our second cam focusing on cutaways and secondary shots (tightly zoomed into our subject’s faces to give their stories more raw emotion). We want to keep the backdrop as clean as possible to ensure minimal distractions from the points discussed in the interviews

ACT 4:  HEEDING THE CALL
Inthwaso (initiation) is the very reason that this concept for the film came to be. Our DP, Dino Benedetti’s cinematic eye giving an interesting take on shots of Thwasa’s (initiates) going in to initiation. Depictions of various ceremonies and tying them all together to form a view from the Thwasa’s perspective. We introduce the following interviewees: Gogo Esme, Gogo Malepena, Gogo Muhlavasi Emma Kejoe & Gobelas’ from Mpande’s representing ama Ndau and Mnguni who detail their journeys as well as taking through their various practices

