";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:537:"I intend to make use of symbolism to drive this story, there are lots of items that were used in the slave trade era that I can match up with today so that this project can reveal that the soul reason for slavery and migration of today is strictly for business which is stemmed by greed, power and laziness. This project will seek to juxtapose involuntary and voluntary migration. My artistic approach is to weave the story in a manner that depicts the greed that exists in these business venture in a subtle but creative cum poetic way.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:111:"So far, Business as Usual has been filmed upto 70-80% both in Nigeria and Mauritania and we intend to film more";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:1991:"Business as Usual is an expośe on the disturbing but growing activities of illegal voluntary migration through the dangerous Mediterranean route. This documentary focuses mainly on the business angle. 

At first, Africans were subdued and inhumanely dragged to become slaves in a foreign land. Fast forward to centuries later, same Africans would do anything humanly possible to end up in same countries, same situations. From the onset, migration rode on the back of greedy men, mostly Chieftains, Kings and men of caliber who would sell their subjects in exchange for mirror, canon guns, gins, umbrellas’ etc.

In recent time, it’s still the same, fixers would transport 120 people on an 80 people capacity boat just to make more money from one trip. But so as not to derail, we will be focusing on why this activity despite how dangerous it is has grown over the years and for where there is a way, there is a will. The way in this case is the first few minutes of the documentary which touches on involuntary migration, this translates to the slave trade era. Due to minimal available footages, we will be depicting the era with 2D illustrations. The illustrations will show the gruesome movement of Africans (slaves) through this route despite how dangerous it was, and still is. 

Cornerstone Eyanem, we will see the plights of slsves through the eyes of a Tour Guide at the Badagry slave museum (Point of No Return) with a couple of students on Excursion 

On the other part of my project, Captain Abou, a Mauritanian fixer/clandestine will take us through a journey of this deadly routes which migrants ply. I intend to see the migrants through the eyes of the fixer, thereby revealing their desperation and reason to travel out of Africa not minding the dangers of the Desert & the Mediterranean and also not minding how much they will spend to get to their destination, if they will ever get there.
In this part of the project, I intend to come up close and personal.";s:14:"representation";s:1364:"BUSINESS AS USUAL was birthed out of deep concern for the massive loss of lives in the Mediterranean.

A lot of stories have been told about Migration, mostly from the migration point of view or the migrant’s point of view, it’s rare to have a Migration story from the business point of view, Business As Usual as the title implies takes a critical look at how money changes hands from the migrant to the clandestine. It also juxtaposes involuntary migration during the slave trade era with the mass voluntary migration in recent times using money as a yardstick. It seeks to reveal the intentions of the clandestine, are they helping, are they genuine or are they there to make their money without minding if lives are lost or not, why do they overload the boats etc., Business as usual will seek to answer these questions.

The whole idea is to highlight the injustice meted out at slaves during the slave trade era and comparing it with the illegal migration of today through the Mediterranean, 'Imagine seeing a rusted Canon Gun on the floor at the Badagry Slave Museum and been told that the piece of metal was used in exchange for 60 able bodied and healthy people'

Business as Usual is an observational film but not in its entirety. The style of the documentary is poetic and cinematic and as the theme is on migration, which connotes movement.
