";s:15:"story_structure";s:1978:"The female body has been many things and nothing through time. She has been bruised, battered, covered up, opened up, cut open. She has been trimmed, watered, pruned like a garden, she has been nourished like a fattened cow; she has flourished and has also withered away. 

This film will be a fascinating combination of archival materials showcasing the culture and practices of old as well as convincing interviews from scholars and emotional cinematography following the lives of our primary character; Lynda Okonkwo.

The beginning of the documentary will feature conceptualization; what is fat? What is beauty? Here, the scholars will take us on a journey through time from pre-colonial Nigeriansocieties and cultures through till modern times to give us a holistic understanding of African cultures surrounding beauty, fat, and the female body.

Next, we will follow the true-life story of our main character, Lyda Okonkwo, backing it up with the voices of selected women, to get their personal experiences of how cultural preferences of beauty have affected their life choices.
What will follow will be the reality of their life choices and how they have been living with these choices especially dealing with peer pressure, body shaming, and the evolving cultural perception of beauty. We will also hear from them, the limits they are going to readjust or reaffirm their bodies. Here, together with the personal experiences, interviews of industry professionals from clinical psychologists to gym instructors, will give us insights into body dysmorphic disorder, the age of digital beauty, the effects of cultural preference and peer pressures on women as it relates to their bodies.

The documentary will end in what I call, the Reclamation. Here, all the elements of the documentary will come together like a crescendo in a symphony. Our characters will talk about their future in relation to their bodies, self-esteem, and their understanding of happiness.
";s:22:"characters_description";s:721:"The documentary will be told through the eyes of Lynda Okonkwo. Lynda has a smile that can light up any room and it doesn’t take much to get a tear to drop from her eyes, perhaps that’s what makes her a terrific actor. She is a 120kg, 6ft, fair-skinned goddess, someone the film industry considers “too fat to fit into some roles”. 
For one in the spotlight, her body is constantly on display and opportunities to shine often evade her, and the little that fall on her laps are ladled with stereotype and body shaming. 
Underneath the wide smile and bubbling personality, is a girl who wishes people can see past the number on the scale and accept her for who she is; a brilliant actor with a beautiful smile.
";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1912:"The desired tone and visual representation of the subject matter are going to be tailored to resonate with and be reflective of the primary target audience; women. The story is character-driven and the subject matter will be explored through the life of our primary character. Interviews from learned fellows on different aspects of the subject matter will also feed into the narrative.

Each interview will be framed in a way that the locations become characters in the story. The locations will play an integral part in strengthening the narrative flow.
Beauty lighting will form the basis of the lighting design of this documentary. The lighting will tell a story; one of freedom and acceptance. The lighting will be flattery and complementary, concealing nothing. However, if a character being interviewed insists on anonymity, we will explore the use of silhouette and light shaping to keep the character hidden. We will go a step further in distorting the voice, not to a level where it will be inaudible but comfortable for the character to express herself.

The sound accompanying the story being told will be in layers. The documentary will open with a poem, glorifying the female body and the struggles it has endured over time. This poem will be accompanied by compelling images to lure the audience into the world they are about to experience. The emotional beats of the story will be accompanied by melancholy music to reel the audience in. Other explorative parts of the documentary will be complemented by soulful, alternative RnB.

The documentary will be made up of interviews, re-enactments, archival videos, and pictures much for the visual appeal of the audience. Because of the unavailability of certain footage, there will be a re-enactment of scenes by professional actors. The actor’s performance, however, will be as realistic as possible, in line with the flow of the story. 
";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1621000337_1.png";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:5:"50000";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:4:"5000";s:12:"totalApplied";s:5:"20000";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:5:"45000";s:10:"budgetFile";s:22:"2021/1621001775_1.xlsx";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:20:"PRECIOUS IROAGALACHI";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"2";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-07-02 20:11:31";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:16;O:8:"stdClass":54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"126";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"127";s:4:"name";s:25:"We, People of the islands";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"90";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:184:"In 1965, in a secret operation, a group of 31 young Cape Verdeans, embarked for Cuba, to receive military training to free the country. A history of ideals, convictions and betrayals. ";s:15:"story_structure";s:1557:"Cape Verde was a Portuguese colony and, within the African context, it is a country known for not having fought for its independence. This version of the story is told from the point of view of the colonizer.
The space for the struggle for the liberation of Guinea Bissau and Cape Verde occurred in the forests and savannas of Guinea Bissau. According to the people's aspiration, Amílcar Cabral, leader of the armed struggle and of the African Party for the Independence of Guinea Bissau and Cape Verde - PAIGC- and ideologue of the independence of the two countries, considers extending the armed struggle to the islands of Cape Verde.
To this end, it begins to mobilize Cape Verdeans scattered throughout the diaspora and forms a group of 31 young people, mostly students, including Pedro Pires, Júlio de Carvalho, Maria Ilidia, and Agnelo Dantas, who decide to embark on an adventure in order to participate in the armed liberation struggle in Cape Verde.
These young people are then sent to Cuba, where they live in complete hiding, and for two years on the island, 1965/67 are subjected to intense military training, with hard hours of guerrilla and artillery training.
With the murder of Che Guevara, the strategy changed and the group ended up not landing in Cape Verde. But, they realized that they could contribute to the liberation of Cape Verde, participating actively in the struggle in Guinea Bissau. Later on, these selfless Creole guerrillas formed the Cape Verdean nation and became influential figures in the country's political life.";s:22:"characters_description";s:1694:"Today, Pedro Pires is the president of Instituto Pedro Pires, an important institution in Cape Verde that promotes leadership training. He was the leader of the Cuba group and even became President of Cape Verde. He is a charismatic figure and considered a historical commander of the national liberation struggle.
Commander Júlio de Carvalho is nowadays a businessman in the trade. He was former Minister of Defense, in the early years of independence he lived in Guinea Bissau and was very dear to the Guinean population and Cubans. At the time of the mobilization, he was studying Chemical Engineering, in Coimbra. He fled Portugal because he had heard that Amílcar Cabral was going to be in Paris. 
Commander Agnelo Dantas, lives the peaceful life of a retired state military officer. He was the youngest of the group, part of Cape Verde at the age of 17, full of revolutionary ideas and to avoid Portuguese military service. His dream was to fight to expel the colonizer from his beloved homeland. After the fight, he was the Chief of Staff of the Armed Forces of Cape Verde.
Maria Ilidia, currently lives in Portugal. She was the only woman in the group. Early on, she begins to realize the differences created by colonialism. It was in the middle of World War II and troops were stationed on the island where she lived, but the Portuguese soldiers and the Cape Verdean soldiers were separated, even the food was different. At the same time she sees her father being beaten and imprisoned, she grows up to fear who had white skin.
In “Nós, Povo das Ilhas” what we are going to do is to enter the intricacies of this bold and daring operation, but little known and publicized.
";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1979:"How to tell an episode of a country's official history? How to film emblematic and influential figures from Cape Verde, detaching us from the repeated journalistic narratives that build a cold heroic discourse?
We decided to embark on the adventure of telling this episode, using two central elements: the interviews and the archive. When making the teaser we realized that our characters are people very used to the formal interview; and for that reason, when analyzing this material later, we decided that the interviews of the film would be made from a more intimate look. 
We want to interview these characters in their homes, or on the symbolic stages of the war and the early years of independence (today empty spaces and many of them abandoned). Taking these characters to their center, it is a way to return to the core of emotional and emotional memory. We believe that we will reach these non-places of memory, where the characters can question themselves and make themselves known in another way.
To guide this narrative within more personal and intimate space, director Elson Santos will be the narrator that will introduce the “voice” of Cape Verdean youth, who inquires about their past. 
This questioning from a personal perspective will lead the viewer to follow Elson, not only during the interviews with the characters but also in the relentless search for archival material to support this story.
The archival material, which is found only outside Cape Verde (in Portugal, France, and Cuba). The fact that it is so difficult to access the historical memory of a country, is a problem common to all African youth, it will then be an issue that will accompany this archive research. This essayistic and reflective tone will accompany the entire film, as a way of deconstructing the heroic propaganda narratives.
We intend to invite the viewer to question deeply about the value of memory while getting to know the intimate side of all these characters.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1618207835_1.jpg";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:6:"178615";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:5:"45405";s:12:"totalApplied";s:1:"0";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:6:"133210";s:10:"budgetFile";s:21:"2021/1618208905_1.pdf";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:10:"Lara Sousa";s:12:"project_role";s:8:"producer";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"2";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-07-02 20:11:43";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:17;O:8:"stdClass":54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"127";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"126";s:4:"name";s:24:"Le spectre de boko haram";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"70";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:172:"
