 the past, camels are now better suited. ";s:15:"story_structure";s:1187:"Climate Change is a serious problem causing havoc in different parts of the world in different 
ways. In Kenya for example, farming patterns have changed as most farmers depend on rain 
fend agriculture, the rivers, lakes and oceans are either shallower or fuller and the water is 
becoming warmer destroying marine life.
In the Northern part of Kenya, pastoralists are suffering. Their goats and cows have been dying 
in hordes whenever drought strikes provoking them to change tact and shift to keeping camels.
Pastoralists communities are now putting more emphasis on camel rearing or shifting from 
other livestock species to camels (A climate change resilience strategy) which are more drought 
resistant for milk and meat production. 
Unlike cows and goats, camels can go for up to two weeks without water and still have constant 
milk production. 
Herders who have shifted from cow rearing to camels are now selling twice as much milk as 
they used to sell before. Working with cooperatives enables women to spend more time with 
their families as well as do other businesses. 
FAO Kenya estimates that drought kills 50%-80% of cow herds and only 10%-16% of camels. ";s:22:"characters_description";s:547:"Herders - These are the people who take animals to the field as they look for pasture and water 

Women keepers - These are the women who milk camels and take milk to the collection centers 

Camel milk processors - These are the centers that receive milk in lange numbers and process it and package it in different quantities 

Food lab - Here, we will seek to know the nutrition value of camel milk 

County Livestock Department - This is the government department incharge of livestock

Food and Africulture Organization (FAO) Expert ";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:671:"Filming will take place in Marsabit, Isiolo, Samburu, Nanyuiki and Nairobi. We will follow the herders into the fields and see how far they walk and what they go through to feed their 
animals. We will follow cows and goats and camel herders then be specific on the camel herders. 
We will then show women milking camels and taking their milk to a collection center and show activities at the collection center.
