 aimed at local and international audiences. The plan is to use the series as a tool to assist people at different levels of society to grapple with the big threat that the climate emergency presents to humanity, bio-diversity and sustainability of life as we know it in Southern Africa. 
 
Intertwining the stories of people who are living at the forefront of the changing climate in Southern Africa, we show how it is those least responsible for this crisis that are most adversely impacted. And in a region where every degree of warming will make a vast difference to how well future generations fare, the series tracks the journey of individuals and movements striving to bring down greenhouse gas emissions. Yet in this region, where the mineral energy complex has shaped the economy, as Naomi Klein would say, ‘This changes everything’.
 
While we draw on the knowledge of African climate scientists to break down the causes of the crisis, the thrust of the series is the eight unique but interwoven, character led storylines, taking place in Namibia, Mozambique, Zimbabwe, Madagascar and South Africa. Concluding a year of research and development in communities where the combined effects of climate and social crisis are rapidly reshaping daily life, in each case the POV will be that of people leading the charge for a sustainable future. In this, we offer the gift of the collective wisdom of activists, youth and women’s leadership, and indigenous knowledge systems. While we focus on the most important climate justice priorities in Southern Africa at the moment – drought, food security, a just transition from fossil fuels, and making safe the air we breathe  - the central thread of HotSpot is questioning how we got here and how we navigate our way into a future where we live, consume and produce in a way that supports and regenerates the natural world that we depend on for survival.
";s:22:"characters_description";s:1992:"Madagascar: Theo Rakotovao is an internationally acclaimed musician from the Mikea people. When he hears that an Australian mining company aim to mine in his town, he becomes one of the leading faces of the opposition. 
 
Mozambique: Celia Macamo is an academic whose mission is to help restore the Mozambique coastline. Jacinta Laissone’s responsibility is to implement a new Climate Action Plan for the city of Xai Xai. Can these two mothers persuade enough people to get behind this life saving work? 
 
Zimbabwe: Admire Gwatidzo, a permaculture farmer and community coordinator grows food in abundance for over 15 years in food insecure and drought stricken Zimbabwe. Can he replicate his methods? 
 
Namibia: Ina-Maria Shikongo, a young mother of three, spearheads an international campaign against oil drilling in the delta. 
 
South Africa: From Soweto, to the courtroom to Parliament, Francina Nkosi, a mother of four living next to Medupi coal power plant, Alex Lenferna, the brainchild of the Green New Eskom campaign, and Promise Mbilo, an eco-feminist, enviro champion and a key applicant in a deadly air court case against the South African government, build a Just Transition movement from the bottom up. 
 
Kolisa Sinyana is a vivacious young oceanographer, whose self-confessed passion is communicating the science of climate change to ordinary people. But what does this mean for a young black woman in South Africa, one who has fought poverty and patriarchy to make her mark as a marine scientist, as she projects into a future that is less than certain?
 
LGBTIQ+ youth activists Raeesa Mohammed and Gabriel Klaasen are in different ends of the country, finding relief in climate activism. When they meet a unique friendship is born out of shared hopes and fears. There is an urgency in their  POV that is compelling both to young black audiences, and to older viewers who cannot help but feel complicit in creating the problems that the young will inherit.
";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:2009:"Using a format of six TV-hour episodes, the series follows eight storylines each led by a set of connected characters from across Southern Africa, that have a specific motivation and something to achieve. Each of the storylines centre around a physical place – a town, a forest, a borehole, a mine – or a cause or right that people are defending or fighting for. Audiences must care about these characters, and empathise strongly with their mission, their survival, or success or failure in what they set out to do.

Style - Our interviews with the characters will be in situ, often outside or in the spaces the protagonists inhabit or work in. The style of filming will allow for intimate moments with the characters, in their home and personal life, using verité hand-held style of filmmaking. 

It is important that through the main storylines, clear information about the climate science is presented, and why urgent and dramatic shifts need to happen across the region.  The interwoven stories draw strongly on nature-based solutions, local knowledge and ideas, and eco-feminist thinking which helps shift our connection to the environment. We want people to understand that our natural environment is not just a resource to exploit, but to realise that the environment is us. How can we support that idea? 

Shots of nature - life giving forests, rivers, estuaries, wilderness, freshwater as a celebration, earth and soil that hold our food; and the power of nature to break, erode and cause devastation help us connect to the natural world. Each storyline holds a trace of the living world and that thread needs to be tangible in the visuals. 

Visual motifs – For each storyline, a parallel recurring visual motif mirrors this development over time. A natural element – be it a polluted river, a plot of farmed land, a section of coastline – is filmed over the production period presenting the growth, the decay, the loss, the filling up or emptying of that piece of environment. 
