name";s:26:"NAITAKA BANGO (Mzee Ngala)";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"70";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:145:"'Naitaka Bango' is a photographic memoir following the legendary creator and founder of the East African 'BANGO' music, Mzee Joseph Ngala Katana.";s:15:"story_structure";s:2003:"BANGO is a music style created and made popular on the East African coast by Mzee Joseph Ngala. It fuses traditional Portuguese music genres, Arabic influenced taarab music, jazz and music genres of Kenyan coastal Bantu speaking tribes. This music resembles Latin America and Indian Ocean islands, Seychelles and Mauritius, styles of music.

From his humble upbringing during the colonial period, to his first introduction to classical instrumentation and his music general band life experiences, Mzee Ngala’s journey to the discovery of Bango music is covered in detail.  

The film follows Mzee from his early education during the colonial times and gradually stretches into his introduction to music. It will integrate his family and professional life highlighting the struggles endured to discover the unique African tune in Bango music. 

This melodic documentary portrait builds up towards the climax of a RE-UNION concert full of his fans, where Mzee Ngala holds a Life Achievement performance alongside his former band mates and children.  
Outline
•	Early Life
Covers Mzee Ngala’s childhood in Mombasa born in October 1935. We deal with his education, family background, and his formative years. We learn the history of his hometown, Frere Town and Fort Jesus.
•	Introduction To Music
Mzee’s as he begins to discover his interest in music. It will cover his early employment before quitting several jobs and retirement at Railways Kenya to finally chase his dream of becoming a musician.
•	Band vs. Family Life
We learn of the names and history of all the bands Mzee transverses before he finally goes solo. We discover the challenges he underwent and how he invented the Bango music style. We re-connect him with his former bandmates and also get to know more of his love life as we build up to the reunion concert
•	Current state (Legacy)
Mzee Ngala’s current situation in his retirement home renovated by the county government. He is a loved and adored legend.";s:22:"characters_description";s:1728:"Mzee Ngala was born in 1933, in a small ward called Frere town, in Mombasa,. The ward, which used to be a depot for slaves for the colonial period, is where Mzee encountered his first music lessons and still lives up to date. 

Mzee Ngala performed in the past with famous groups such as the Hodi Boys and was also the founder and bandleader of the 1960s and 1970s famous group Bahari Boys. He started of playing the clarinet and later matured to be talented saxophonist. He quit a number of jobs to pursue his dream of becoming a musician. Alongside his friends he composed a song “Naitaka Bango” which gave the music genre its name.

He was faced with a series of band hopping and breaking during a time when reggae music was making its way into Africa. Like any other musician he was often engaged in band wrangles. However, he believed in the developing a new music genre for his people and decided to start a fresh band with his own children whom he had taught how to play different kinds of instruments over a period of time. His son, Jimmy Ngala, carries on his father’s legacy with a modernized style using his Tamaduni band.

Mzee Ngala is known for composing theme songs for local Television soap operas of the late 90s like “Kisulisuli” https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S7IDOyaXBqs.   Up to date, Mzee is always contracted to compose and perform songs for newly weds. 

At 85 years old Mzee Ngala, arguably the oldest Kenyan musician, is slowly aging like fine wine. His music is highly celebrated and listened to by millions of audiences regionally. He is often contracted to compose wedding songs for couples and even play in concerts & restaurants. He wishes to be re-united with is old memories
";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1937:"The film being a music & concert biopic, a full-length interview with Mzee Ngala will comprehensively give information of his past, present and possible future. Strategically structured questions will be used to lead the narrative to our preferred destination.

Many of Mzee Ngala’s photographs will be presented in concurrence with the time period being explained.  Archival footage from local T.V and ratio stations are vital with most of Mzee’s footage and sound recordings in custody of media stations. B-rolls, but not limited to establishing shots, will be taken of various historical locations at the coast where Mzee Ngala lived, worked and socialized.

Black and white dramatic re-enactments will backdrop Mzee’s narration of some major events that have already happened. Using creative face-hiding shots, we shall relive a bit of Mzee’s youth life seeing him learn how to play different instruments. The lighting used will have a mixture of both artificial and naturalistic approaches in order to craft a sense of harmony between his personal and professional life. 

Music tracks and songs composed by Mzee Ngala will be crucial to the storytelling. In a gradual and vibrant tempo, either a track or an instrument being played will occasionally enhance the story, giving it a melodic tone that brings nostalgic memories to the audience. 

All footage will be shot in full frame on a Black Magic Pocket Cinema 6k camera. A colorful glossy grade on the documentary will keep the audience in a happy celebratory mood. 

Interviews with musicians, influencers, relatives and even politicians will help the audience understand Mzee, both from a personal and professional level. Insights of bands from the 80s such as ‘The mushrooms’ interweaved with current bands e.g. ‘Sauti Sol’ and solo artists like ‘Nyota ndogo’ will highlight the greatness of Mzee Ngala and his influence to recent music trends.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1620140967_1.pdf";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:5:"42000";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:5:"10500";s:12:"totalApplied";s:4:"5000";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:5:"31500";s:10:"budgetFile";s:22:"2021/1620141162_1.xlsx";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:18:"Bill Jonnes Afwani";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"2";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-07-02 20:15:47";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:32;O:8:"stdClass":54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"258";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"500";s:4:"name";s:11:"The Syrians";s:6:"p_date";s:3:"100";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:196:"The crossed intimate portraits of three desire driven Syrians living in Lebanon at crucial human phases (birth, grown-up, death) composing a mosaic of life and troubling the concept of identity.  ";s:15:"story_structure";s:2017:"More than nine years after the protests began, Syria has known one of the largest exodus of its modern history, especially towards Lebanon, a country itself under high tension and sharing a particular history with neighboring Syria. 

Now, Syrians constitute one of the largest displaced populations in modern history (8 millions people inside the country and 5 millions outside). Despite having opened its borders Lebanon’s policy towards them has hardened since 2015, making renewals for temporary residence permits almost impossible. 

For instance, Lebanon does not recognize the “right of the soil”. Syrians living in Lebanon, in most cases for long years, are in a difficult situation: most of them are illegal residents, dozens of thousands of new- born children on Lebanese soil are stateless and if a Syrian dies in Lebanon, his/her body is often not accepted in cemeteries. What I essentially want is to capture the desires, goals, and dreams, the relentless humanity of those people enduring an inhumane situation, unwanted wherever they go.

For about a year and a half, I started conducting remote research from by home country of Tunisia, to draw out the first basis of the project. The film received development support from the IDFA Bertha Fund, the Arab Fund for Arts and Culture and the Beirut Film Station (Goethe Institute Lebanon), which allowed me to make several trips to Lebanon and feed my research. 

That’s how I met Fadia, Leena, and Abou Ala who started telling me about their lives. Thanks to these encounters, I was able to conceive a first narrative framework for my project and a provisional structure.

The film will be composed of these portraits at different moments of life, and put together, they will create a storyline which will go from pregnancy to exile and emancipation. These characters make up the pieces of a much more complex puzzle. They represent the multiplicity of humanity, at a time when displaced populations are often considered as statistics.";s:22:"characters_description";s:630:"Leena is 6 months pregnant and lives in a tower in the north of Tripoli, Lebanon, along with a dozen other Syrian families ; Abou Ala lives in an informal settlements in the Bekaa Valley region, he is obsessed with the fact to bury his elderly father with dignity ; Fadia dreams of immigrating to Canada where she will be able to start hormonal treatment to become a woman.

The three of them have fled war-torn Syria and found refuge in Lebanon. Through their portraits emerge the fractures and paradoxes of a region under high tension as each one of them is struggling to achieve a goal and realize a dream in a hostile exile.";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1640:"The film is to be shot mostly in Beirut, but also in the coastal cities of Tyr (south of the country) and Tripoli (in the north) in order to properly cover the nationwide humanitarian tragedy that is happening there. Lebanon has become the equivalent of an open-air camp now that the number of Syrians refugees on its soil is almost reaching 1.5 million people. Scattered across the country these men an women live in “informal settlements” and “collective shelters” but also in disused and abandoned buildings, in huts in the middle of fields or in garages and deposits.

Regarding my filmmaking approach, I intend to do most of the shots with handheld camera. The different portraits will also be part of a larger mosaic of people and families living in different situations and different locations in Lebanon. During editing, long shots will punctuate the film, as a way of reporting on their marginal status. Shots that will cross the line of conventional editing, as if to retain as many gestures, sensations and emotions as possible.

How can one be filming when he/she is at the heart of one of the most important events in terms of international issues?
This represents to me a visceral question, since my body is being involved in the process as a filming and testifying tool. This singular situation calls for a cinematographic reflection and invention. My documentary will not be informative nor didactic, but rather intimate, close to the people I will film. It will pay attention to what surrounds them - Lebanon as a territory and as a society. It focuses on deconstructing rather than constructing a discourse.
";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1620642137_1.png";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:6:"172438";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:6:"123000";s:12:"totalApplied";s:5:"50000";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:5:"49438";s:10:"budgetFile";s:21:"2021/1620730363_1.xls";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:7:"ismaël";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"2";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-06-22 10:38:42";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:33;O:8:"stdClass":54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"262";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"519";s:4:"name";s:32:"Untitled 'Umra Omar' Documentary";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"90";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:202:"At a moment of historical change in Kenya’s ancient Lamu archipelago, a lion-hearted mother of two puts her organisation and family-life in jeopardy to run for Governor & fix a broken public system.  ";s:15:"story_structure";s:2016:"Umra Omar was raised in Lamu by her grandmother before studying and working in the US as a psychologist. She returned home in 2014 just as Lamu was attacked by Al Shabab fighters, leaving dispensaries & schools in the area deserted. That’s when Umra founded Safari Doctors to provide medical services to the communities cut-off by the conflict. 

After 6 years growing the organization beyond expectations, the Lamu streets are overflowing with trash while the state-run medical facilities have deteriorated further, often empty of personnel, medical supplies & even running water. Umra’s frustration with a corrupt local government has finally reached breaking point, and her decision to run for Governor (the highest seat of power) in the upcoming elections is already disrupting the male-dominated political order, who’ve never had to contend with a female candidate so vocal about their failing leadership.  

Situated on Kenya’s northern coastal border, Lamu is famous for its exquisite Swahili architecture, 14th Century old town & untouched tropical islands. Isolated & neglected since independence, Lamu is the third poorest county in Kenya. But change is imminent with a $25B infrastructure project featuring a China-funded mega-port, industrial city, coal power plant and oil pipeline. This has triggered a scramble for land by outside businessmen, as tensions rise with the locals whose fisheries and mangrove forests are being destroyed, along with a growing Kenyan and US military presence trying to gain control over lawless southern Somalia.

It is amongst this geo-political quagmire that 37-year-old Umra is transitioning from humanitarian hero to a bare-knuckled political organizer. With no political experience or corporate backing, amidst a growing onslaught of misogynistic vitriol, this film is a close-and-intimate chronicle of Umra’s decision to dance with the devil, revealing the huge personal costs to her and her family as she enters the scrappy arena of Kenyan politics.";s:22:"characters_description";s:2022:"Umra Omar, the eldest of 3 sisters, grew up barefoot in the remote Pate Island village of Tchundwa, raised by her grandmother, a matriarch who had 8 husbands and 18 children.  Reunited with her parents in Nairobi after they finished their studies, Umra was awarded a high-school scholarship at Atlantic College in Wales before studying neuroscience & psychology at Oberlin College in USA. After her first placements in Washington DC and New York City, she returned to Kenya in 2014 for a job with Open Society Foundation, before the Al Shabaab attacks in Lamu compelled her to start Safari Doctors.

Umra’s father, Omar Bwana is an anomaly amongst Swahili men for educating his three daughters at an ivy-league level. As a young man, his work in preserving Swahili culture impressed the paleoanthropologist Richard Leakey, and together they founded Lamu Museum, excavating the many ancient Swahili ruins dotted around the archipelago. Omar was a prolific political organiser in the 1950’s, forming the Shungwaya Party to begin agitating for Kenya’s independence. In 1972 he was selected by President Moi as a nominated Member of Parliament before becoming chairman of National Museums of Kenya. Umra’s biggest cheerleader, he has been quietly pulling strings behind the scenes & calling upon his political contacts to open their doors to his daughter.

Other characters in the film include Umra’s 2 children Azza & Bwana. Umra’s chief-of-staff Ismael Bwana & her campaign manager Sande Oyolo, who is closely aligned with William Ruto, the current Vice-President of Kenya, and favourite to win the presidency in 2022.

Umra’s mother and two sisters are also of interest. Since Umra’s announcement to run, they are asked for money everywhere they go, and the prices for a boat-taxi, motorbike or even a meal at a restaurant have now doubled. Already uncomfortable with this disruption to their lives, they are not yet agreeable to be in the film, but we hope this will change as the campaign progresses";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:2019:"UMRA is an intimate and personal feature-length documentary following the life of a political candidate over 18 months leading to election day.  We will mix verite scenes & informal interviews filmed with deeply saturated colours and a sharp, cinematic visual approach in the style of an international noir spy-thriller, set amongst the enchanting fishing-village of Lamu.

Iconic for it’s fusion of cultures over thousands of years of Indian Ocean trade between Africa, Arabia, Europe, India and China, Lamu’s coral fortresses hold ancient secrets that pass with the wispy perfume of fully-veiled women in black buibuis. Donkeys bray throughout the day as traders dust away sand from their stalls of tropical fruit & spices. The Imam’s 5 daily calls to prayer resonate through the narrow cobbled streets & an influx of men in white kanzus enter and exit the many mosques for their time with Allah, a refreshing purity amongst the otherwise stifling heat.

The relaxed observational scenes of Umra and her family at home will contrast the intense pressure and chaos of the political campaign & rallies. We will play visually with a dual consciousness which Umra describes as a mental separation of her real life self (known only to her friends and family) from her public ‘poster’ persona (alone and isolated, where people demand everything from her like a walking ATM).  We also want to visually explore Umra’s background in neuro-science, psychology and public-health, and her love of chess, to articulate a deeply cerebral awareness of human nature, and how that translates into her political strategy.

Musically the film will feature an original score co-composed by director Maia (a prolific Kenyan musician) together with local swahili musicians who carry the richness of Taarab music, fusing middle-eastern scales with stringed orchestras and deep african drum syncopation.  The score will also be electronic, gritty and industrial at times, to build and release the story’s tension & drama.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:132:"Filming has continued in May and June, several more foundational scenes have been captured.  Currently concentrating of fundraising.";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:2008:"UMRA is a story that needs to be told now, and needs to be told well - with a passion and tenacity that mirrors the protagonist. Our first 2 features (The Letter, 2019 and How to Build a Library, in production) also feature unbelievably strong women who spoke to us so deeply that we kept at it for years because these are the stories the world needs to see.

Our third feature, UMRA is our most ambitious and risky project yet: with a short time-frame, in a location where logistics are expensive, security is volatile, and a protagonist who is ruffling some very powerful feathers. Since November 2020, we’ve travelled to Lamu 3 times and managed to film and cut a fundraising trailer without any financial support, while simultaneously releasing and producing our first 2 films.

Having captured several key scenes of the foundational stages of the campaign, our primary goal has been to form a deep relationship with Umra built on trust, honesty and mutual respect.  Having known Umra and her sisters since 2015, we were able to jump straight into filming with her and her kids, staying at her place to immerse ourselves into her life and enjoy many long conversations into the night to understand each other better and discuss the overwhelming need for a political revolution in Kenya. This is the foundation on which the next 18 months of filming rests, together with our cultural awareness, speaking the language and our own Swahili-roots (Maia’s father’s family lineage connects back to Lamu sultan in the 1800’s, Umra’s father even has a book about the life of Maia’s Great-Grandfather).

Lamu is a heavily walled city, insular and encrypted to most outsiders.  Umra and her family are unique in their openness to a film crew, and between the strength of our relationship, her love of the camera and a strong pride to showcase her culture and homeland, this film will provide an insight into swahili culture, family-life and local Kenyan politics that few films have ever achieved.";s:14:"representation";s:1943:"As we see time & again, Kenyan superheroes like Umra are ultimately powerless in a broken system, and the film will highlight the immense price paid by those who try to change it. A strong dramatic engine is inherent in Umra’s mission, along with a clear ending. The 2 main narrative challenges we anticipate are (1) accessing her political opponents, and (2) capturing the protagonist’s more ruthless side which may contradict her clean public image. By employing a good local fixer we can overcome the 1st & the 2nd will be solved by remaining independent, which Umra understands is a vital ingredient to making the story realistic & compelling. Umra cannot survive the journey unscathed, and she is open & honest about us filming the risks & moral compromises she must make to win.

So far we’ve shot everything ourselves (Maia: sound / Chris: camera). On our 3rd, current trip in Lamu we’ve brought a DoP from Nairobi to build familiarity with the subjects, as we prepare to give birth to our first child in August 2021. A grant from DOCA would allow us to ensure the DoP & fixer can continue capturing the unfolding events from July to October. We then intend to rent a house in Lamu long-term & make a second base to continue filming the campaign through to August 2022. 

The film will be shot in 4K with cine prime lenses to achieve a cinematic vitality.  We’ve been inspired by films like “Knock Down The House”, “War Room” as well as Samaher Alqadi’s feminist inditement of the arab spring “As I Want”, and Sam Soko’s “Softie” which lay bare the flawed Kenyan political process.  We want to push the documentary genre by emulating the framing, suspenseful editing, music and aerial cinematography from film-noirs like “Chinatown” and spy-thrillers such as “The Girl With the Dragon Tattoo” & “Bourne Identity'' which we feel can help elevate the film’s aesthetic and commercial appeal.
";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1621241680_1.jpg";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:6:"752099";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:5:"17315";s:12:"totalApplied";s:6:"145000";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:6:"734784";s:10:"budgetFile";s:0:"";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:10:"Maia Lekow";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-06-19 19:06:11";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:34;O:8:"stdClass":54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"267";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"323";s:4:"name";s:12:"TENA NA TENA";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"90";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:44:"We've never really lived, but only survived.";s:15:"story_structure";s:1926:""Tena na Tena" is a film about parenting that dives into the choice, commitment and sacrifice of breaking the cycle of hardship in Nairobi, a city that can embrace and raise you or chew and spit you out. 

Our story will focus on Shiku a mother who does everything to keep her child off the streets and Donga, a child who was kicked out by the mother to be raised by the streets.

Our first character is Nairobi. She symbolizes a place with the highest form of financial redemption but when you scratch deeper, the risks attached to succeeding in the city become clear. She nurtures, shelters and feeds millions daily, the difference is how she interacts with her children.

Shiku is a mother of two and a low end sex worker who lost one of her sons through extrajudicial execution and who currently tries to transition to becoming an upstanding member of society.

Donga, once a violent criminal on the police’s most wanted list, now wears many hats; tour guide, taxi driver. He is actively pursuing music and seeks to offer a better foundation to his son by being a positive male role model.

Donga and Shiku have known nothing but bare minimums. To the backdrop of excess, they have received nominal guidance, childhood, education, love, shelter, you name it. Circumstances that have informed their past and present pursuits. Having lost a great deal along the way, the hunger to move from reduced qualities of life keeps them searching for better times.

Our characters are making changes to their lives from their regrettable pasts to hopeful futures, with their children as catalysts.

We follow them as they modify their lifestyles to assimilate to their quests for legitimacy. Previewing what it takes to be reinstituted into the same society that had denied them access to resources and skills from the very beginning, as well as showing their efforts to provide what they lacked to their offspring.
";s:22:"characters_description";s:1256:"Shiku - 
One of many sex workers who patrol the dimly lit Nairobi night streets. Midway through her pursuit, she received damning news about her eldest son; a 19-year-old boy who was shot twelve times by a notorious killer cop in Eastleigh, Nairobi. Now left in limbo, and with the advent of Coronavirus restrictions, she does ‘regular’ jobs while searching for closure from her loss to keep her second born son, Imran, off the streets and avoid him suffering the same fate.

Donga
Boisterous and driven, a proud father, budding and talented musician. Donga’s life has been shaped by bullets and blood. From the age of 8, Donga was raised by the streets that left him with no option but to beg, steal and eventually become one of Nairobi's wanted criminals.
 
To earn a living in hopes of funding his musical pursuits, he guides paying tourists through the city he previously tormented as a gang member; showing them a haunting previous life he is trying to separate himself from. Between surviving in a cut-throat town by yearning to opt out of the street life and the frustrations of booking studio space with nothing more than the promises of passion, what remains essential to him is the need to present a better father figure to his son.
";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1567:"We want to portray our city and its inhabitants oscillating between beauty and realism, capturing the beauty of situations and the fragility of the people.

Whenever our protagonists interact with their children, they reveal a calmness. The camera reflects this in still imagery of planned compositions. The anxieties and movements are of human causes and experiences, something we show through a handheld camera when we are on the streets. This accentuates the grit and realism of Nairobi's fast pace. The lens will expose the raw developments of the characters as they unfold from the comforts of their personal spaces to the rat race society with minimal staging.

The film will use a mix of cinema verite, direct cinema and interviews to paint pictures of Shiku and Donga’s experiences of living and parenting in Nairobi. Every scene and image presented will be handled delicately and with a lot of dignity. The motion picture will oscillate between the past using symbolic poetry showcasing the lives of Donga and Shiku’s first born son, and the present, depicted by beautiful imagery of their current state. 

The audio will consist of ambient recordings of the environments, city and surroundings from footage captured and from the narratives of interviews conducted from the subjects.
The main voices and focus of the picture will be Shiku and Donga who will weave us in and out of their daily life proceedings, introducing us to characters who advance subplots relating to or complementing their journey to breaking free from the loop of hardship.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:156:"We recently completed the Follow The Nile development & mentorship program 2020/2021 which was followed by a successful pitch at DokFest Munich in May 2021.";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:577:"My society has an INCLINATION to sensationalize people living odd lives and odd jobs based on person perception. This film invites its viewers into the lives of Shiko and Donga with a frangible perception. It hopes to reverse the desensitizing narratives derived from fear, disgust and negative moral judgments like the ones I harboured before the journey to making this film.
The protagonists unapologetically characterize a rare mental fortitude to be who they are. Their lives invoke subliminal conversations like childcare, morality, mortality and love in today's society.";s:14:"representation";s:1687:"I feel that as human beings we all have a cycle that we are caught up in and want to break at one point in our lives. This is all in hopes of entering an easier loop that promises a better life than the one we are currently in. 

When I first heard Donga's story, I took a moment to reflect on my reaction when a street kid comes to my car window to beg when the traffic lights turn red. I mostly didn't even look to the side with the fear that I'd make eye contact which would intensify the begging. I never had a moment where I stopped to ask what their story was or to even accord them the respect of responding to their knock on my window. And this is all from the social stigma I've unconsciously carried towards street kid. 

Then, I met Shiku. The first footage I watched of her reached out to me because she spoke with honesty and vulnerability I would not have expected out of a sex worker. Again, because of the social stigma and negative narratives I've carried around prostitution, which never allowed me to view the humans behind these branding. Shiku was morning the death of her son and I could hear the undertones of self blame and doubt as she reflected on how she raised her son.

This film embraces some very bold themes and bears a universal outlook as it invokes universal conversations around parenting, love and mortality in today's society. 

Donga and Shiku's pursuits for a better life expose a larger societal issue of its over-dependence on broken systems that promise people redemption while consistently devaluing human lives. Who dies and who gets to live and how many times do we have to start over to break away from the cycles we are trapped in?";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1620985087_1.jpg";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:6:"338829";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:0:"";s:12:"totalApplied";s:0:"";s:11:"totalPening";s:0:"";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:0:"";s:10:"budgetFile";s:0:"";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:10:"Cindy Mbae";s:12:"project_role";s:8:"producer";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-06-19 17:25:00";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:35;O:8:"stdClass":54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"278";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"562";s:4:"name";s:34:"République, Pétrole, Révolution";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"90";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:192:"Abdoulaye est un jeune étudiant en analyse et politiques économiques. Il se retrouve dans la rue, avec ses camarades du mouvement FRAPP pour lutter contre les inégalités et l’injustice. ";s:15:"story_structure";s:2065:"Le 2 juin 2019, la chaine britannique BBC diffuse une enquête de Mayeni Jones, intitulée : « Sénégal : Scandale à 10 milliards de dollars ». Dans ce reportage, la BBC affirme détenir les preuves qu’Aliou Sall, frère cadet du président de la République Macky Sall, a touché des pots-de-vin en 2012 pour l’attribution de deux concessions pétrolières à l’homme d’affaires Frank Timis. 
Ce reportage de la BBC déclenche un soulèvement populaire au Sénégal. Les jeunes sortent dans la rue et se mobilisent pour protester contre le gouvernement de Macky Sall car ils estiment intolérable que les dirigeants sénégalais et les multinationales s’enrichissent au détriment de la population. Parmi ces manifestants, il y a Abdoulaye Seck, 21 ans, étudiant en troisième année de Licence d’analyse et politiques économiques à l’Université Cheikh Anta Diop (UCAD) de Dakar. 
Abdoulaye Seck est très engagé politiquement. Il est le président des étudiants du mouvement FRAPP, Front révolutionnaire anti-impérialiste populaire et panafricaine. Depuis les années 2000, les conditions de vie à l’université sont devenues de plus en plus précaires à cause de la mauvaise gestion étatique. Les étudiants dorment dans les couloirs sur des matelas. Il faut se réveiller à 5 heures du matin pour pouvoir se doucher à temps. Pour lutter contre cette vie dure à l’université, les étudiants se sont mobilisés pour mettre en place un mouvement citoyen, le FRAPP. Ce mouvement veut réveiller les consciences des populations et mobiliser autour de la lutte pour une justice sociale.  
C’est dans ce contexte que le pays bascule dans la révolte en mars 2021.Le sentiment d’injustice et les frustrations provoquées par la crise de la pandémie dégénèrent en violentes manifestations : il y a 10 morts et près de 600 blessés. L’enjeu du film repose sur la trajectoire d’Abdoulaye et son impact dans la réalité : Abdoulaye peut-il aller au bout de cette lutte ? Cette lutte peut-elle mener à une révolution ?";s:22:"characters_description";s:1295:"Abdoulaye Seck a 21 ans. Il est le fils d’un cheminot, syndicaliste et militant de gauche. Il a grandi dans une famille où la conscience anticoloniale est très forte. Il habite à Keur Massar, un quartier populaire de la banlieue dakaroise, où les conditions de vie sont catastrophiques. 
Il est en troisième année de Licence d’analyse et politiques économiques à l’université Cheikh Anta Diop de Dakar. Il est très engagé politiquement. Abdoulaye est au cœur de mon film. 
Si j’ai choisi Abdoulaye parmi tous ces jeunes, c’est sans doute en raison de son charisme et de sa sensibilité. A mes yeux, il incarne la jeunesse. Il se sent très concerné par l’avenir du Sénégal. A sa manière, il se bat pour son pays tous les jours. Malgré son jeune âge, il est déjà considéré comme un leader. 
Le fait de partager le point de vue d’Abdoulaye nous amène à réfléchir sur la situation du pays, la vie quotidienne de cette jeunesse : les difficultés, les rêves, les aspirations. En filmant Abdoulaye, je montre symboliquement le vécu quotidien de cette jeunesse.
Abdoulaye est le personnage auquel le spectateur s’identifie. Son engagement et sa détermination donnent au spectateur les éléments de sa propre réflexion sur la lutte de cette jeunesse. ";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:2026:"En tant que cinéma du réel, République, Pétrole, Révolution puise ses fondements dans l’histoire du temps présent. C’est un film qui se construit sur la base d’un mouvement de contestation sociale d’ampleur inconnue depuis le mouvement « Y’en a marre » de 2012. Il s’agit donc pour moi de suivre le fil de l’histoire et de filmer l’évolution d’Abdoulaye et du mouvement dans une perspective qui se veut sensible. Je suis les évènements avec simplicité en accompagnant mes personnages et je les filme dans cette réalité qu’ils cherchent à faire évoluer. Cette logique me permet d’être authentique, d’être au plus proche des personnes et d’inscrire le projet dans l’actualité sur un temps long. Filmer Abdoulaye en mouvement, c’est filmer un possible avenir en construction.
L’espace du film est son territoire, ou ses territoires : la ville de Dakar, sa banlieue, parfois les régions. Si le récit est clairement ancré à Dakar grâce à Abdoulaye et au FRAPP, le film montre aussi à quel point le mouvement est implanté en banlieue et comment les principes du mouvement essaiment dans tout le pays à la faveur des luttes initiées aux côtés des communautés locales. Mais Dakar et sa banlieue restent au cœur du film, plus qu’un décor, presque un troisième personnage qui serait nécessaire à la concrétisation des rêves d’Abdoulaye et de ses camarades. 
