For centuries, the African woman's history is not accessible as that of the western woman. Even in documentaries, the history of the African woman barely gets a mention. We call to mind the groundbreaking documentary, The Ascent of Women by Amanda Foreman. Yes, many African women were not very pleased that Africa women got minimal coverage. That is an indication that the African woman's story is for Africans to tell. 

This film decolonizes history and situates it in a social-cultural context. It studies how ancient African women withstood and fought against slavery and European influence for decades. How did they survive? How did they run a viable economic society while raising a family? It brings to the fore what the contemporary African woman needs to know about her heritage, culture, and tradition. It interrogates why the Africa woman seems to be out of touch with who she is. It also examines how religion and colonialism introduced patriarchy to Africans and at what point gender oppression festered across the continent.

Structurally, the film weaves an in-depth look into the lives of these matriarchs and their present contemporaries across Africa. They come together to share their stories revealing unknown information as never seen before. Shooting in a cinema verite style, we provide a fascinating window into the characters' lives, capturing and documenting their experiences and knowledge. It looks at the different regions to understand the cultural similarities and differences, the advent of gender oppression, and how to defy societal limitations. The film covers the pre-colonial African woman, the divinity of the African woman, the culture of shame, and the feminist movement. 

";s:22:"characters_description";s:2006:"Four women gather by the fire pit to share powerful stories of some of the pre-colonial African women behind the most powerful empires like the Makeda of Ethiopia, Nefertiti of Egypt, Queen Anna Nziga of Angola. And that of the women who championed some powerful movements in Africa like Yaa Asantewa of Ghana, Nandi of South Africa, Moremi/Amina of Nigeria, and others of not so royal background. The documentary unravels how these women existed, looking at their different life stages (birth, initiation, rites of passage, religion, education). It uncovers how these matriarchs resisted the colonial masters, and defied societal limitations in a male-dominated world to thrive, carving their paths to success. The stories probes if colonialism and the introduction of western religion birthed gender inequality.

The women take us on a journey into the Africa woman's spirituality and the rejection of western ideals of divinity. It tells the story from the African cosmology perspective located within specific cultures on the divine woman. They unravel how the African woman communed with God before western religion, touching on specific areas such as (the body, the mind, meditation, prayer, and self-awareness). Their stories shed light on the feminine deities that exist in Africa.
These women take us on a pleasurable journey about the African woman's sexuality and how it evolved with time. It traces the origin of female circumcision and its effect, in addition to the myth about menstruation and orgasm. It delves into controversial areas such as female husbands (women marrying women for their husbands/partners) and the LGBT society (women who love other women). Examining these issues pushes boundaries and makes the conversation inclusive.
It examines the argument among academics that feminism is too radical to be African and does not capture the African woman’s realities. They tell the stories of extraordinary women who are creating their paths and shattering the glass ceilings.";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1451:"Daughters of Africa is a feature-length documentary, which uses the narrative of Five women’s journey, stories, and history to engage viewers, inform, entertain, educate, empower, and drive the story forward. Their powerful dynamic story takes place over several decades and across some African continents. Professional narration is used between acts and to set the stage for the ongoing discussion. Key narrative scenes take place in practical locations, some by the fire pit and under the moonlight depicting the beautiful African scenery. As some of the women share their stories,  we hear the trusted voices of historians and experts as they affirm convictions or disagreements and offer different perspectives that engage the audience throughout the film, it shows scenic, historic locations, archival footages, and reenactments. The film is augmented by voice-over, family photos, and videos, etc. 
The colour palette shifts from the contrast of earthy brown, orange, black to green and warm yellow. To achieve the best cinematographic picture qualities, two full-frame cameras will be used with accompanying lighting facilities. The sound will be recorded externally, using the boom, multi-channel field recorder, and lapel microphones regulated with appropriate sound equipment for ultimate audio output. Tracks, sliders, drones, DJI Ronin, jibs, and other motion picture gadgets will be used in achieving an enduring moving picture film.
