";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1044:"The everyday vérité narratives involve observing characters in therapy sessions, recording studios, time with family and loved ones and use of personal archives. 
These will be interspersed with historical footage of black exploitation and systemic racism as well as moments in history when black famous people have spoken up about mental health or died from mental health related issues that will be projected and allow participants to give reflections on the effect these have had on them personally. 
 
Water will be a recurring motif that for me symbolises rebirth, cleansing, healing, transcendence and peace and constant flow and change. 
 
The film is weaved together through poetry narrated by a renowned South African poet. The poetry will be written specifically for the project. It will be supported by original music that specifically captures the spirit of the film created by Canadian musician/academic/poet Ian Kamau. 
 
