aware of the natural beauty of the night sky that exists just above their heads - but that they are unable to see for themselves - was a harsh reminder that humans have become extremely disconnected from the natural world, and need to find ways to reconnect.

After doing extensive research, I got in touch with Professor Thebe Medupe who was very keen to get involved in any way possible. He is passionate about raising a generation of “scientifically literate” young South Africans, in order to equip them with the knowledge and skills necessary to make sustainable, and ecologically responsible choices into the future.

The story structure will mimic the fluid way in which San people tell stories. However, certain archetypes will be present in the film. The first part of the film will focus on inspiring. We will then delve into the problems at hand - both environmental, socio-economic and political. We will explore how political forces fractured the San communities and seriously hindered them. Similarly, we will explore how Apartheid in South Africa fostered the idea that “black children don’t belong in science”. Facing the challenges that our characters have faced, we will begin to unpack how these can be remedied and we can begin to trace a new path forward.

The film will also include both Medupe and our San characters’ observations of how society is run today, and how modern day people (particularly those in first world countries) have come to be completely disconnected from the natural world. We will get our characters views on how this can change, and why it’s so critical and urgent to implement these changes.

A new way forward will be presented - one which urges people to reconnect with their roots. ";s:22:"characters_description";s:541:"Professor Thebe Medupe is an astrophysicist living and working in Johannesburg, South Africa. Growing up in a rural village in South Africa, he would look up at the night sky as a child and become inspired to study the stars. Growing up, he built his own telescope, and later went on to study at the University of Cape Town. Thebe is now a professor and working as the deputy dean of his faculty. He has built his own space observatory in Mahikeng, Gauteng and works with South African children to inspire them to become involved in science.";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1941:"This is a story about the human relationship with the cosmos, from a uniquely African perspective. The film will open with a beautiful timelapse of the night sky, with Prof Thebe Medupe’s voiceover explaining how life on earth comes from stars.

The following scene will take us into the Kalahari desert. We will hear traditional San music along with closeups of the San dance ritual - feet on the ground, hands playing instruments, eyes looking up into the sky, and fire flickering against a dark background. Our San character will explain the significance of the stars in the San culture. He will talk about how for their community, living in perfect harmony with the land has been their way of life for hundreds of thousands of years. We will include shots of the San men tracking an animal, or the way they read the signs of the environment such as looking at the movement of sand and plants. Drone shots will establish the setting of the desert. We will then move into the challenges that the San face, using creatively styled cutaways as a metaphor.

The film will allow our San characters to shape the narrative with an African voice. It will be more fluid than the typical Three Act Structure.

We will then return to Thebe Medupe as he talks about his upbringing and his journey towards becoming a professor of astrophysics. We will have shots of him in his home in Johannesburg, as well as shots of him showing us around his space observatory that he built in Mahikeng, Gauteng. We will also film Thebe in his classroom, working with children as he teaches them astronomy.

The film will comprise of sweeping drone shots, landscape and star timelapses, slow motion shots, professionally lit interview setups, emotive and astral sound design with indigenous notes influenced by Hans Zimmer’s Interstellar composition, and characters who inspire a deep fascination and wonder for our planet and its place in the universe.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:138:"Our application for a filming permit in Botswana has been submitted successfully and we expect to get the go-ahead to film in August 2021.";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:1865:"There has never been a more critical time in history for humans to reconnect to the environment. If we are to survive as a species, we need to stop seeing ourselves as separate from nature. Right now, it is more critical than ever to drive home the message that human beings depend on healthy, in-tact ecosystems for our survival. We are part of nature.

The San people of the Kalahari serve as a perfect example of how humans have been living in tune with the landscape for millennia. The fascinating, awe-inspiring night sky serves as a link between all humans that have ever lived. From both a scientific and a traditional perspective, life on earth comes from stars, including us.

Lying on the ground in Sutherland, South Africa, looking up at the night sky, this simple yet highly complex idea hit home for me. It was at that moment I decided this film needed to be made. I realised that if more people had the opportunity to experience the splendour of the night sky, perhaps that would inspire them to feel connected to nature, and to want to protect it.

Receiving a grant from National Geographic Society for this project was a massive honour, and helped me truly believe in the weight of my idea. With National Geographic backing me, I am more determined than ever to bring this film to life. With some extra production funding, I am confident that we can tell this important story at the high standard at which it deserves to be told. 

I tell stories that convey undertones of empathy, gentleness, subtly and unique leadership. I am interested in reaching audiences on an emotional level, while bringing them closer to science in an engaging and deeply awe-inspiring way. A unique balance between education and entertainment, I believe, is the key to inspiring an audience to engage with the content long after the credits have started rolling.";s:14:"representation";s:1196:"Pre-production is well under way for this project. We have secured some funding from National Geographic Society, and with some extra funding, we will be able to produce this film at the highest possible standard.

Our filming will take place in three locations: Mafikeng (South Africa), the Central Kalahari (Botswana), and Sutherland (South Africa). We have a local fixing company, Okavango Filming, on board for our Botswana leg of the production. They have a long-standing relationship with the San community of the Kalahari and understand the dynamics of the community deeply. They are helping us with obtaining film permits, and will be there to mediate between the film crew and the San people.

We aim to film Prof Thebe Medupe in August 2021 in his hometown where he built his own observatory in Mahikeng, Gauteng. From there we will move on to Grasslands, Botswana, to film the San people and their stories. In September, we will take a trip to Sutherland and film Prof Medupe there, where we will look at the science that is taking place at the SALT Observatory, and how the Prof is involved in this work. We will also film as many star time lapses as possible while in Sutherland.";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1620915731_1.pdf";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:8:"24507.87";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:4:"9614";s:12:"totalApplied";s:1:"0";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:3:"NaN";s:10:"budgetFile";s:0:"";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:12:"Tessa Barlin";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-06-16 21:48:40";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:41;O:8:"stdClass":54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"291";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"578";s:4:"name";s:18:"MY BIRTH MY CHOICE";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"75";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:200:"Giving birth via Caesarian section is on the rise in Kenya, with more speculation around the hospitals and medics pusing for it to gain more profit. But what can a future mother do to empower herself?";s:15:"story_structure";s:1078:"This documentary idea came to mind when I was going through my own pregnancy in 2019 and trying to find a suitable birthing option for myself and my baby. But almost everyone I knew, from family members to close friends to strangers, had delivered via C-Section. This got me wondering how it became that giving birth, something  that our bodies are designed to do naturally, is considered no longer possible without medical intervention for such a majority. Why Science is invariably the solution to getting babies out and how highly invasive procedures have become the norm. I didn’t understand that.

My quest to getting the information that would help influence my choice was not only eye opening but also stirred the desire to empower other women as much as possible. Something that is largely lacking since most people trust medicine and medical practitioners so much more than they trust their own bodies, their own rights or their own free will. And, are heavily paying the price both financially and physically. I sincerely hope this film helps to change all that.
