s social and family life, now depending on therapy to improve and being part of a support group together with fellow victims, Wahinya has not yet fully healed from what he underwent when he was arrested.

In the film, he takes us on a journey from childhood to university, as he narrates how he ended up at loggerheads with the government of that time. This is not displayed chronologically but instead intertwined with scenes of this current life.

Besides highlighting just a portrait of Wahinya, the story deeply captures the pursuit of justice and recognition by the forgotten ‘second liberators’ of independence in Kenya – a pursuit that has been ignored by sitting governments for years. The film follows their journey as it unfolds, gives room for the accused to respond and finally leaves it for the people to conclude.";s:22:"characters_description";s:1195:"Wahinya wa Boore is the main protagonist of the film. He is a 66-year old charismatic man who currently resides at his rural home in Nyeri County in Kenya, and often visits his family in Nairobi. He does consultancy work on human rights and social justice issues for various organizations and also engages in small-scale farming.

He is a former political detainee and a torture survivor, having spent 6 years in incarceration and 46 days in the former torture chambers located at the basement of Nyayo House in Nairobi. And though many years have passed since he was released, he hasn’t fully recovered psychologically and also ails physically often due to the brutality he endured.

However, he is a resilient man who does not give up easily, as is visible in his pursuit of justice for the atrocities he underwent. His character embodies the spirit of the National Victims and Survivors Network (NVSN), an association that champions for the recognition of victims of human rights violations in Kenya. Wahinya is the Secretary General of the association and a firm believer in fighting for what is right. He is bold and vocal when it comes to challenging authorities that oppress people.";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1636:"The film is mainly observational, where we follow our character over the period of production. We will have multiple character interviews in different locations and showcasing different experiences that our character undergoes. As we have complete access to him, the film will feature a lot of intimate scenes of his personal life at home, with family and with friends. We intend to capture the deepest emotions possible. One of the major sequences will be the annual visit to the former Nyayo torture chambers. Here, we have our character walking among other former detainees who have already formed an association together, and they freely interact, reminding each other of their experiences during those days. He also walks into the chamber where he was jailed as he describes the physical structure of the cell and the purpose for each section. This culminates into a moment where they gather together, light up candles, sing songs of freedom and make chants. Afterwards the leaders of the association give updates on how far they have gotten with their pursuits and later disperse.

Another sequence will be his frequent visits to the hospital where he goes for therapy. After checkup he goes to the nearby market where he meets his childhood friends who have great admiration for him, as we see and hear from their interactions.

Also, as the association keeps on its pursuit for justice from the government, frequent court proceedings, parliamentary petitions and protests will create a stronger narrative for the film. These will be vital scenes as they depict the resilience and courage often needed in seeking reparations.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:45:"There are no pertinent updates at this point.";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:861:"The human rights and social justice agenda in Africa have been shaped by different political systems over the years. Whereas there have been great achievements, there have also been failures that have left many wounds on those it affected. This film tells the story of a resilient pursuit of justice in an attempt to address some of these wounds. It is therefore important and timely as it is a history that can easily be forgotten. With many of the characters in the story being of old age, their passing will mean the death of this piece of history too. This story will be fundamental in revisiting the ideas of democracy on the African continent and more importantly, what tenets of it include free speech and upholding of human rights. The more we learn of and from the past, fixing what can be fixed, the less we are likely to not repeat the same mistakes.";s:14:"representation";s:991:"Human rights has always been a global issue that needs to be addressed and there is a strong need to have conversations around them. Wahinya and his fellow comrades are a representation of a global movement that needs to be heard and reparation offered to them. Ever since I learnt of his story and his strong character derived from his perseverance and steadiness in seeking justice, I knew that this would be a powerful story that will not only cause a ripple impact effect but also encourage more people who have undergone similar injustices to come out and share their stories as the first step to healing. This documentary film is fundamental now especially when it comes to addressing factual issues of the past that have otherwise caused harm especially to those challenging unlawful acts enforced onto people. The inclusion of different generations in this compelling story plays an important role in urging future generations to fight for what they believe in and for what is right.";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1621360580_1.pdf";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:5:"28012";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:4:"1420";s:12:"totalApplied";s:1:"0";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:5:"26592";s:10:"budgetFile";s:0:"";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:14:"Samuel Wanjohi";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-06-20 18:44:35";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:51;O:8:"stdClass":54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"348";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"734";s:4:"name";s:16:"THE GREEN EMPIRE";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"60";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:161:"In a place where any open space is either a garbage site/ shanties, a group of youth is in a quest to turn the community space cum garbage site into Green Space?";s:15:"story_structure";s:1776:"‘The Green Empire’ is a documentary film that follows a group of youth living in Mathare Slums and 