is stuck in a destructive loop.
 
Noku is a 23-year-old hopeful and has ambitious dreams but the prospects are limited, and there is pressure for her to leave for South Africa as an immigrant. She’s also frustrated with how conversations about progress in Matabeleland are all hinged on the past. Particularly the state-sponsored atrocities that took place in the 1980s. 

Chris disagrees. Since the government killed his father in 1983 - he believes that he has been living under a curse placed by the angry dead whose bones have been scattered across the country. This curse has tainted any efforts to progress in life. Now living as a struggling migrant worker in neighbouring Botswana, Chris is adamant that only a change of guard and the reburial of his father will lift the ‘bad omen.’
 
Shari is obsessed with bones. She believes she can heal people such as Chris by exhuming the remains of their loved ones. She tries to do this while navigating her identity as a white Zimbabwean in a divided country, and the realities of her uncomfortable and violent colonial heritage.
 
Until 2017, all these desires felt impossible. But then the unimaginable happened when President Mugabe was ousted. That spurs the beginning of public exhumations. With Shari’s help, Chris manages to return his father’s bones to his rightful homestead.

But as racial and tribal tensions are at an all-time high, Chris desperately wants to return home, but not empty-handed. Meanwhile, Noku starts volunteering in hopes that she will eventually be gainfully employed. Shari faces a personal tragedy of her own; can she find acceptance in a community designed to shun her?

Will any of them be able to move forward when so much of Zimbabwe remains stuck in time?
";s:22:"characters_description";s:1986:"Chris Nyathi is a 60-year-old man living and working as a migrant worker in Gaborone, Botswana. The oldest of 11 siblings, he is the head of his family and has carried this burden since 1984 when his father was suddenly killed by the military during the Gukurahundi atrocities. Despite his efforts to financially provide and guide his siblings, he becomes convinced there is a curse on his family, which is the cause of all their economic, professional and personal struggles. When he finally manages to return his father’s bones to their rightful place, Chris still feels cursed, pandemic lockdowns in Botswana leave him unemployed and feeling out of sorts. He tries to rebuild but his new quest becomes, like his father in many ways, to return to the place he came from Matabeleland.

Sixty-three-year-old Shari Eppel started her career as a psychologist working with victims of state-sponsored violence in Zimbabwe. When trying to counsel the victims of the massacres seemed insufficient, Shari discovered the only way to bring healing to the people of Matabeleland would be to first bring healing to the dead. She does this with the hope that the future generation and her granddaughter, in particular, will grow in a Zimbabwe that has come to terms with its past. This proves very tricky for Shari who also has to grapple with her identity as a white Zimbabwean living in a very racially polarised country.

Nokuthaba Neshiri is a 23-year-old hopeful living in a largely marginalised and economically depressed Matabeleland. Her dream was to go to university, but it’s been years since she left high school and her family still cannot afford to send her to school. But still ambitious, she tries to get a job and work her way up, but the prospects for her are not promising. She wants to stay and invest her efforts into her community but she’s growing frustrated “When will it be our time?” she asks and argues that the country needs to stop obsessing over the past.";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1150:"‘Healing the Dead’ is primarily told through verité scenes and intimate moments of Chris, Nokuthaba and Shari’s lives, supplemented by archival material. In Gaborone, Botswana we see Chris’ daily life as an immigrant while he carries the burden of being the head of the family and household. In Bulawayo, Zimbabwe, we film scenes with Shari and watch her navigate through communities in rural Matabeleland as an anthropologist and her life as a grandmother. And in urban Nkulumane, we see Nokuthaba active in his community. These scenes will be supplemented with landscape and atmospheric footage of dry savannah of south-western Zimbabwe where the massacres took place. This will be juxtaposed with stylistic footage of colonial buildings, vintage cars, and dilapidated factories throughout. This will provide a metaphorical exposition of how Zimbabwe is stuck in time and how the country has frayed over the years. Where appropriate I will provide personal reflections through the form of a tour of my country as a way of reconciling the home I grew up in blissfully ignorant with the place I’ve come to know as an adult and storyteller.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1620976553_1.jpg";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s: