The film interacts with Peter Mutiso who was a student in form 3 at the time the fire smoke filled dorm and a pain on his leg which would later on be a scar from where he got burnt.
Towards the 20 year anniversary of the fire we follow Mutiso confront the outcomes of the fire and what his journey of pain loss has entailed.
Will he reconnect with his family? Seek counselling? What does he want from life?
When the fire happened, Ng’ao remembers waking up to smoke which was blinding his vision and fire. At this point he asked God a question, “God what do I do?” in Kamba and he remembered advice from his dad. 
Leading up to the 20 year anniversary of the fire, we follow him as he brings his former classmates together for the celebration and as he confronts his family struggles growing up and how this has affected his current outlook of life.
Did the nightmares of seeing people burning stop? And has the guilt of losing his close friend John become more bearable? Did he actually heal or is this a coping mechanism? Will he be able to meet Dr Violet and express his gratitude to her? Will he successfully organize and bring his former schoolmates together for the 20 year anniversary? What next?";s:22:"characters_description";s:1959:"Peter Mutiso now a teacher, husband and father, remembers waking up and seeing one of his dorm mates running towards one direction and never came back and with this he ran the other direction. He notes the first 10 minutes of the fire breaking out was the most crucial. He remembers the day of the fire quite vividly. He remembers waking up to a fight for survival.
He has been haunted by this scenes for a long time and says his life took a turn to the worst after the fire, he took sometime before going back to school and his grades dropped drastically, he always wanted to become an engineer but settled on becoming a teacher. The father of three unlike his friend and schoolmate Ng’ao never received any sort of counselling and has since dived deep into alcoholism and because of his work doesn't live with the family. Towards the 20 year anniversary of the fire we follow Mutiso confront the outcomes of the fire and what his journey of pain loss has entailed.
Daniel Ng’ao now a youth advocate with a political dream, husband and father, remembers running to the exit of the dorm and he kept on running. As he was running he remembers seeing other students running around while on fire. He was confused and helpless and had no idea how to help them. He did not realize the extent of the tragedy until the morning when he saw bodies being carried in the dozens into a Red Cross lorry.
Growing up Ng’ao had a close relationship with his dad. He goes by Ng’ao Daniel in a bid to continue his dad’s legacy. The Ng’ao name. He is the last born in a family of 14 kids. He however did not grow up being close to his mother and despised women growing up for he thought his sisters were being treated better than him. He has lost a brother to suicide who drank poison and killed himself.
His slogan is, “To give people a genuine reason to cry when he dies.” He says, “In this world you don’t need everybody you just need one person.”
";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1892:"Defying Ashes takes an introspective look into how society treats tragedies and the Journey of pain and loss through the eyes of Ng’ao and Mutiso. 
Weaving together moving interviews and rare archival footage, Defying Ashes will portray, for the first time on film, the individual journeys of the survivors of this fire tragedy, their pain, and the enduring power of resilience and will. 
Through the lens of these two survivors, the documentary film, Defying Ashes, will examine, with affection and insight, what it means to experience tragic loss. Following the struggles of these two men who at the time were just boys, it will give audiences a window into the turbulent tides of the last 20 years. 
Their stories will help us understand our story as a people. Fire being a perfect metaphor for the world of tragedies and the value society (African) places on counselling and how we treat victims of tragedies. 
Leading up to the 20th anniversary of the fire, Defying Ashes by contrast will turn the story on its heels and provide a refreshing twist, by showcasing the victims perspective and putting a survivor at the center of the story. It will anchor the tale of two boys(now men) who experienced the same tragedy but their lives turned out completely different from each other. 
When did we get that way and how? Defying Ashes dares to suggest answers. It dares to probe into these people's lives. It dares to suggest that the choices we make and those made by our families and the society around us makes us who we are. 
Our documentary, though, will do more than provide historical insights. At its core, it will probe the shifting relationships between friends as their dreams and realities respond to the winds of change sweeping through their lives. 
Through interviews and the use of rare film footage, photos and other archival material, and following the characters. ";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:90:"Defying Ashes is an official selection to take part in the Durban Film Mart Finance Forum.";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:1116:"When I was about 10 years old one of our neighbors tried committing suicide by pouring paraffin on her body and setting herself ablaze, a few months later I was with my brother inside our house when he, unfortunately, got burnt with boiling water and ended up spending close to 8 months in hospital, the burns were too severe that my young self could not be let inside the hospital wards until he was let to come home eventually.

Although I was only 10 years old when all this happened, these images have stuck in my head my entire life. Now imagine being in a dormitory full of your classmates, people you see daily, play with, eat together banter each other and then one morning just like that 67 of them are brutally killed by a ravaging fire started by your fellow colleagues.

Defying Ashes takes an introspective look into how society treats tragedies and the Journey of pain and loss through the eyes of Ng’ao and Mutiso.
Defying Ashes will portray, for the first time on film, the individual journeys of the survivors of this fire tragedy, their pain, and the enduring power of resilience and will.
";s:14:"representation";s:502:"Defying Ashes is a story of resilience, overcoming traumatic grief and tackling life. In life we are always inspired by stories of triumph. We are encouraged when we hear stories of people who went through a journey of loss: Financially, Spiritually, Emotionally, Physically etc and how the journey to overcome and emerge from their challenges shaped their lives. These stories tend to leave us saying, “If they overcame that, I can overcome my challenges.” This is what Defying Ashes communicates.";s:21:"representation_upload";s:25:"2021/1620977271_1-org.jpg";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:6:"169658";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:5:"22651";s:12:"totalApplied";s:1:"0";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:6:"147007";s:10:"budgetFile";s:0:"";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:10:"Joan Maina";s:12:"project_role";s:8:"producer";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-06-18 21:54:24";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:57;O:8:"stdClass":54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"366";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"785";s:4:"name";s:13:"The Vanishing";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"90";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:202:"One evening in 2012, my mother Mariama vanished. With my camera, I’m chasing, the prints she left behind, within me and my family. The Vanishing retraces the dazzle and distress of this African woman.";s:15:"story_structure";s:2013:"A woman has vanished.

This beautiful medium-sized black woman, born the year of our independence, in 1960, lived intensely: a long eventful life of 52 years, between several continents and aspirations. She is my mother.

In August 2012, she flew from Paris to Dakar, the capital of Senegal. On the eve of the Korité, the holiday marking the end of the month of Ramadan, it is presumed that she traveled towards Guinea by taxi. After that, nothing. Mariama literally disappeared.
This Essay-Documentary is not a biography, nor an analysis or investigation into her disappearance, but rather a reflection on permanence and impermanence. This film was born from the need to answer this question: "What do we leave behind?”. What traces, what prints can a life leave behind? Aside from the memories? What is really left of us and of our passage on this earth? 
This quest on my mother's personality will be done with testimonies I will collect with my camera, by retracing who she was thanks to the sensory traces she left around her on her relatives and her family. From my two grand-mothers, to her three husbands, along with my siblings and her close friends, all people that I’m filming are either members of my family or friends of my mother. Many of them have been wounded by life and society, especially the women. 
I will articulate the passage from one stage of My mother’s life to another, not chronologically, but by analogy. I will use different material such as historical and intimate archives - pictures, sound, video, and my drawings and animation to “substantiate all that is insubstantial”. 
The backbone of my film is the letter in voice over that I address to my mother. This letter is written in very peculiar tones, in which I intend to use intimacy and humor to reflect the exuberant and colourful life of my mother. 
In the landscape that is our collective memory, I’ll chase my mother’s tracks. And through this portrait, I’ll sketch the path that led me to cinema.";s:22:"characters_description";s:2003:"This film will be told in part through interviews I will conduct involving family members and friends of my mother. Here is a description of three very important of these characters : 

My Maternal Grandmother, Aissa Ly

Aissa was born sometime around the 1940s. Her exact age is unknown. She is a Peul. Her family is one of the noble families that guided the Toucouleur kingdom in Tooro. In my grandmother’s family, men are all imams or religious guides, from father to son. 

Aissa was an extremely strong and independent woman for her times and social class. A true feminist. She had seven husbands and eleven children.

My mother and grandmother never got along, but still, they could not live without each other for very long. As for me, I instantly fell in love with my grandmother. 

Today, Aissa is a plump old woman who looks more like a turtle. She does not believe that my mother is dead. She thinks she vanished on purpose, and is secretly living in the United States. She has kept many photos, of herself, my mother, and the family. 

My Father Elhadj Thiaw

My father never stopped loving my mother. He even tried to marry her a second time, when my mother divorced her second husband. Although we were separated until I was 27 years old, he was always supportive and loyal to me, when he found out my mother had vanished. He is the only one who has helped me to find out what happened to her. Both of us believe that my mother is dead, probably murdered by her last husband. 

My stepfather, Michel Roseau:

Aside from his dream of becoming a professional guitarist, my stepfather had two other passions: photography and motorcycles. He liked to shoot and print his own color portraits, and he was fairly talented. His life as a wealthy expat was smooth and easy, until he met my mother.I don’t what he thinks of the Vanishing of my mother. It’s been almost 18 years since I saw him, and we lost touch. Seeing each other again is likely to be a bit uncomfortable. ";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:2025:"I see The Vanishing as a drawing, a sensorial object, a tactile epic tale on screen. My film will display features akin between the personal story and the documentary essay. This hybrid form reflects the lives of both my mother and myself; in other words, our cultural blends. The shape of my film will be created from four items: 
Filmed Image: Filmed in Cinema-Verite style- the testimony of those who knew and were close to my mother. By filming them, I’m seeking in their memories what she has left to them. And piece-by-piece I will draw her portrait. I plan to interview and film both of my grandmothers, my mother’s three husbands and three other children, and her friends. There will also be archival footage to give a counterpoint with political or historical background. These official archives can be seen as a complement to what I call the “private archives” that our family has kept, of my mother. 

Photos: To collect the testimonies of her relatives, I will ask them to rely on photos of themselves but also those they have of my mother. I am seeking to emphasizes the imprint, we leave behind us, with the interplay with the filmic or photographic component when you’re in the darkroom and the image on the film slowly appears. I will often use a photo as a device, either to evoke memory and speech, or as a medium that gives life to my mother’s body over the course of time. 

Drawing: Drawing was an essential part of our life as a family. Drawings and paintings allow me to “materialize” all that is immaterial about my mother’s life. I’m using animation in certain poetic moments which are either referring to dreams, mind mood and to the non-visible world that is part of my Senegalese culture. I’m using an old handmade technique, a rostrum camera. 

Music: Music was the artistic basis of my mother’s lives and resilience. Instead of asking a composer to write a soundtrack for the film, I shall choose seven emblematic songs to make the Sound Track of Mariama’s life.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:547:"The project is still at the same phase production wise. In the past month we had the opportunity to prepare an important scouting filming that will take place in the coming weeks as well as a development workshop involving the director, the editor Niels Pagh Andersen and animator Marie Opron that will take place at the end of the summer. 

The purpose of these events is to push towards the end of our development phase and have a final scripted treatment. 

Following our production schedule, we will enter our financing phase accordingly. ";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:2004:"How will I make an invisible visible?When I examine my mother’s journey, from her birth to her late decisions, I see a never-ending struggle.

She had to fight prejudice and discrimination of which she was a victim for being a woman with a modest background, African and Black on top of it all. In societies like these, to cope with the multiple discriminations against you: you must find and create in yourself multiple types of resilience, to overcome and transcend these visible and invisible violent forces.

Violence can be used against oneself or, on the contrary, for oneself. But in every case, this energy must travel, be channeled, and pour out. Because violence is in flux; it is never static.

Every time Mariama confronted violence, she resisted with her own weapons. Sometimes with the quest for knowledge, with access to schooling and the Arts. At other times with political activism. Finally, when she dealt with even more complex forms of violence, she resorted to spirituality to survive. It guided her in dark times.

My life is a prolongation of hers. I exist primarily through the foam of her imprints. As a Mauritanian- Senegalese who lived in Europe, in the answers I mustered to resist the same struggles she endured.This is why I decided to tell my mother’s story in light of such a special prism. When I analyze my filmmaking desire, I can also analyze the rhetoric of violence and art as resilience, resistance, and redemption. 

Filmmaking and Vanishing are two opposite poles on a single axis. Vanishing means that one is no longer visible or apparent to others, whereas making this film about my mother's disappearance is making her visible to others, forever visible on a film. Implicit in the action of filmmaking is the revelation of my background. I publicly display my own invisibility: by going back to the sources of my own mysteries, demystifying them, and using the Image to reveal them. Making The Vanishing is an act of opposition to the vanishing. ";s:14:"representation";s:1994:"The Vanishing highlights the life of an invisible person, invisible by her gender, skin color, social background and history. Beyond that lies another undisputable truth : her vanishing made her physically invisible to us. She became a shadow, a ghost. This is a beautiful cinematic and human challenge. This film deals with the traces that we all leave behind and is, for that, reason meant to move audiences.

Stories of black women are starting to reach a wider audience. They should no longer dive back into invisibility. This project is a generational story that will speak to anyone interested in African communities and their diasporas. 

The director's approach is to tell us a historical resistance/fight through an intimate point of view combined with collective History, circumventing actual proliferation of set images and unfolding in several countries.

As the project is entering it’s financing phase, and after a development for which Boul Fallé Images gathered several financial supports and industry nods(CNC, Hot Docs, Scam, Ciclic…), our most recent and prestigious recognition is the Visions Sud Est award the project received at the Pitching du Réel in Nyon. To meet the ambitions of the project, we need time. Time of several shootings in different countries. Months of animation with Marie Opron, months of editing with Niels Pagh Andersen. The high estimate of budget is mostly due to the crucial importance of animation, archives and music in Rama Thiaw's vision.

Our coproduction strategy in order to finance the film reflects these realities. One of our primary goal is to make sure the film remains in majority a Senegalese and African production. The co-producers we are gathering at an international scale (Switzerland, Germany, Mauritania…), such as our first partners at Films de Forces Majeure (France) all share this imperative and the importance to make themselves useful allies in solidarity with our fight to keep our patrimony in Africa. ";s:21:"representation_upload";s:21:"2021/1620992715_1.pdf";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:7:"1052979";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:5:"91287";s:12:"totalApplied";s:6:"955191";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:6:"961692";s:10:"budgetFile";s:0:"";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:10:"Rama Thiaw";s:12:"project_role";s:8:"producer";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-06-21 21:11:09";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:58;O:8:"stdClass":54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"375";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"811";s:4:"name";s:20:"Black Women and Sex ";s:6:"p_date";s:2:"80";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:190:"The film explores the tension between black women and the politics of sex. Through the voices of three women who identify with sex differently, in Africa (South Africa, Zambia, and Nigeria) ";s:15:"story_structure";s:1947:"Glow Makitsi (27 years old) is a Transgender woman from South Africa who started her transition in 2017. Glow went to a gay bar she normally goes to with her friend to have a good time, at some point in the night she needed to use the bathroom and went to the Female Bathroom. The doors in the stools don’t close properly so she pushed the door open and the lady inside pushed back at her, she knew someone was inside and decided to wait for her to finish. When the lady came out of the bathroom she asked Glow why she was using the Female Bathroom, and insisted that she should be using the Male bathrooms and this led to a verbal and physical altercation. This led to a court case that we followed with Glow which is one of the many politics that she faces as a Transgender woman in society. Through the emotional labour of fighting for her place in society, Glow continues to stay true to herself and her identity. We follow her as she gets her testicles removed, so she lives in a body that reflects who she is. We follow her in her daily life and find out the realities of no representation for Transgender people which makes her feel erased but also making it known that she will never erase herself, we see this through her work as a model and an activist. 

Olawumi Fakayejo ( 26 years old) is a Nigerian woman who was raised in a polygamous home. We find out how growing up in her home has shaped Olawumi’s views on relationships, gender roles and what a happy home looks like to her. 

Mwaka Magula (29years old) is an Entertainer from Zambia. She grew up with a father that was in the Arts and knows the power of Representation and was inspired to be in the same space herself. She is now one of the lead actresses in Zambia’s first telenovela called Zuba. She speaks about what she knows Representation for black women to be and how she wants to change that representation through the attention that she gets as a celebrity. ";s:22:"characters_description";s:1947:"Olawumi grew up in Akure, Nigeria in a Polygamous home which is very common in those parts of Nigeria. She’s the oldest of her siblings and grew up very close to her mother, and saw the effects of the divorce between her parents when her mother was removed from the home with her children. Olawumi was very close to her mother who spoke very openly about sex, the struggles in her marriage and how important it is to have sexual pleasure. We see the effects of having a sex positive mother and how it’s freed Olawumi
in her life and approach to romantic relationships. Her mother passed away shortly after her marriage from Cancer, and now she’s the closest thing to a mother that her siblings have. Olawumi just finished her first year of marriage which is said to be the hardest, and the first year without her mother. She depends on her husband financially and that comes with some politics, and we see how her Christianity affects the way that she approaches her relationship.

Mwaka is a Zambian Actress, she stars in Zambia’s first Telenovela Zuba, she has her own YouTube channel, works as a Script Writer and Journalist. She knows and understands how important representation is, having grown up with a father in the Entertainment industry. Zambia is a very conservative country, and it stops a lot of women from expressing themselves and feeling liberated. Mwaka has created a platform where she is able to do that with the women in her life, and uses her fame to let other women see her doing it so that they are brave enough to do it in their own lives.

Glow was born in the Free state and raised as an only child by a single mother. She is a Transgender woman that started her medical transition in 2016. She moved to Cape Town after she finished high school and graduated at the University of Western Cape in 2014, she wanted to work in corporate but has found it very hard to get into because of her sexual identity. 
";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1357:"The visual approach of the film will be observational, walking with them in the journey of their lives to see small and big ways they contradict themselves with the things they say in interviews and the way they live their own lives. This will be achieved by following them in their family settings, the way they are at work, the way they are with their friends and the way they are when they are alone. We will focus on one issue at a time so it’s easier to link the politics they have in different contexts, because they will be cut into happening at the same time.

These three stories show Representation for black women in different contexts, starting with a lack of representation for Transgender women, to negative representation for black women, and the lack of representation again for women in African Traditional settings. These politics will be shown at the same time, as the women navigate the tension between them and the politics of sex. We will show them in their individual lives with many politics including sexual violence, the pleasures of sex, their first sexual experiences, religion, tradition, history, activism, money and sex, sex work and the LGBTIQ community in Africa. These stories will move from what they have experienced in the past, to what they are currently experiencing and how they want to be moving into the future.";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:25:"2021/1620908035_1-org.jpg";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:6:"201573";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:5:"58703";s:12:"totalApplied";s:6:"106091";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:6:"142870";s:10:"budgetFile";s:22:"2021/1620915546_1.xlsx";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:17:"Godisamang Khunou";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s