the intimate relationship of Man to Time; the opposition of time standing still in an abandoned village to time passing by men which confront us with our own mortal condition. The story of Quirino is also the confrontation of tradition and modernity, of man’s attachment to the Land, of his relationship with Nature. 

The story takes place on the island of São Nicolau in Cape Verde, in Ribeira Funda, a small village located at the bottom of a deep valley surrounded by high mountains and a rough sea. After a series of tragic events occurred its inhabitants taken by a superstitious frenzy abandoned the village, attributing the tragedies to forces of evil. They all left to settle in a neighbouring village, Estância de Brás. All of them...except one. A man stayed: Quirino. 
For more than thirty years now Quirino David da Cruz, 76 year old, has been the sole inhabitant of Ribeira Funda, the ghost village. 

Now Quirino is moved to the other village would he survive his new surrounding? 
";s:22:"characters_description";s:924:"During all these years, Quirino has refused help from the local authorities and friends to move him out, to these initiatives he has never ceased or respond with pride that Ribeira Funda was the land where he was born and where he will be buried. He survived all these years by fishing and getting vegetables from his own garden. He spends his days gazing at the ocean and the majestic mountains that surrounds his home. His only company is a rooster, a few sparrows and portable, battery powered radio which brings information from the rest of the world. 

But today Quirino, faced with uncertain future and the grueling weight of isolation, disease and old age, Quirino hesitates. For the first time in his life, he’s starting to accept the idea that he might need help of others to survive. However, Quirino is not alone: he lives among his memories and images of a world that existed - and that is no longer there.
";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1687:"The film follows a non-linear narration that embraces the different spaces and temporalities experienced by the main character - solitary - and the in- habitants of the neighbouring village. It will follow Quirino’s steadfast daily life, facing an environment of dizzying beauty and hostility. The documentary also follows the steep path that leads us from the ghost town where only Qurino’s radio disturbs the silence to another wold so far, so close, so full of life. The film travels between these contrasting places, and from desert to animated returns, the film explores the different points of view on Qurinio’s voluntary solitude and his desire to continue his life in the place he has always known or to move to this other place which he perceives only fragments. 
Three different approaches allow us to apprehend the soul that represents this isolation. The first takes a contemplative approach in order to capture the relationship between the character and the environment in which he evolves. The second adopts a more creative style in order to give a feel of the fantastic dimension of this universe. The narration does not hesitate to transport us to a fragmented temporality in which we come to question what’s happening on the screen: is it the present, a recent past, Quirino’s imagination or his memories that recreates the abandoned village of Ribeira Funda? 
The third approach in the extension of the previous one then embraces a more intimate engagement, more focused on the direct feelings of Quirino. 
The second part of the story is complete contrast to what our character is familiar with. This time he is the one observing the life beside him. 

