PATRICIA MAIA
Only 23 years old, Patricia is the mother of a 3-year-old boy and has recentlygraduated high school in Achada São Filipe. She is completely blind on her left eyeand almost completely on her right one.
Patricia lives in São Pedro’s neighborhood, Praia, Cape Verde. She has known rejection from a very young age: first from her father who abandoned her when she was still a baby, then from her primary school teacher, the father of her son, etc.
Even so, she managed to study through ADEVIC, she speaks Creole and Portuguese and some French and English.
Patricia dreams of being a singer. She doesn’t want to be dependent on state funds forever, and wishes to be economically independent so she can have her own house
and raise her son.
She has recently started dating someone new, who appears to be very supportive of her condition and her dreams. She is torn between wanting to be the best mother
she can be to Kenny and actually enjoying being young and pursuing her dreams freely. She attempts to do both.
She is very concerned about her son’s health and wants to try and prevent him from going blind and understand why he has stopped talking. She is the main character and the narrative evolves around her.
TITIA
Titia, Patricia’s mother is completely blind. She was also abandoned by the two fathers of her daughters. She works as Patricia’s mentor and gives us context from her birth and how she was raised.
She lives with her two daughters and her grandson, Kenny.
Titia is very active and is always busy at ADEVIC’s workshops, batuku rehearsals and doing cakes and sweets that she then sells.
KENNY
Patricia’s son, Kenny, is 4 years old and already shows the same symptoms – losing his sight as time goes by. He as also stopped talking recently, which is an alarming sign of regression. He does not have any relationship with his
father and Patricia is the one who raises him with the help of her mother. ";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1263:"“And who will cook?” will be a character documentary and will be shot mainly in cinema verité style. We will follow
Patricia while she prepares herself for “Voice One”, a local TV competition series, which will be the leading thread of
the documentary.
Sound will be immensely important in this documentary because it is the sense that allows Patricia to “see”, so it will
have to be our primary sense to be activated. If there’s a fly in the room we’ll need to hear it before we see it.
Music will also be a fundamental element throughout the film. Not only does it represent a dream for Patricia but it
also illustrates Cape Verde. Therefor it will be present in Patricia’s life in multiple ways – her humming songs, her
rehearsing for the competition, on the radio at her house, on her batuku rehearsals with other blind women and also
as a transition between sequences.
Patricia, like her mother and her older son, has been losing her sight gradually.
In “And who will cook?”, we’ll explore that concept visually through the focus. We’ll begin the film focusing exclusively
in Patricia and her family, having everything else unfocused. As the documentary progresses we’ll increasingly start
focusing on everything.
