They took the first step of bravery against all odds.  They didn’t entertain the colour of their skin or their gender. They lived in a time when being black was almost a curse, yet they were able to rise above that.  They didn’t do it for themselves but for their fellow men who were despised and degraded in every possible way. They set up a stage and today many others can follow in their footsteps. 
These are stories of triumph.  Today South African women can enjoy their freedom and be able openly speak about the challenges they face but before all this, Bertha Mkhize had to be brave. She had to stand up for every woman who came before her and those who came after her. Like Bertha KE Masinga also did something remarkable when he walked into a white only SABC building in Durban and became the first black radio presenter. For the first time black people could listen to their own language and be proud. Another brave man was Simon Mkhize who ran the comrade marathon six times unofficially before he was to be recognised. He loved to run the 80 km marathon but he was black and it took longer for him to receive a green card.  Another brave woman who went against the odds, paving the way for others is Sibusisiwe Violet Makhanya. She became the first black social worker in South Africa.
These documentaries will give us a glimpse of the historical foundations to different disciplines. We shall learn about the participation of black people in different fields in the era where black people were refused participation. These documentaries will open the doors to the world and history of broadcast, sports, literature, business and social services in South Africa. This was the time when one needed to be brave in order to achieve their aspirations. These stories will be intertwined with today’s world in order to understand how we arrived where we are today. ";s:22:"characters_description";s:1386:"BERTHA MKHIZE was born in Embo in 1889 but shortly after, she lost her father. She received her  education at  Inanda Seminary and Ohlange. These are schools where Bertha received her education before she started teaching. She taught until she was thirty years and called it quits in order to pursue her business passion.  SIMON MKHIZE was born in 1942 in Howick. He grew up in a farm in Underberg . He then moved to Pietermaritzburg where he started running at the age of 28.  BUSISIWE MAKHANYA grew up in Mbumbulu in KZN and like all other village girls she collected water from the river and did all other chores that were expected of her. When she was nine years old she attended the Inanda Seminary School for girls. In 1927 she earned a scholarship to study in the US. MAGEMA MAGWAZA was born around 1840 in Zululand to the Ngcobo clan. Magena was also a messenger for Colenso, sending messages to King Cetshwayo. This gave him an exposure to the Zulu royal family and he developed a relationship with the King, who he described as “good, kind and loved by his people”. KE MASINGA was born in 1904 in Mzumbe. The story of KE gives us an opportunity to explore the history of radio in South Africa. The radio in South Africa started in the 30’s from humble beginnings as a platform for the wartime report service, propagating certain ideals and values from a central source. ";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:745:"This will be a five part series but each episode will be treated with the similar style. The films will invite experts and those who were close to the characters to give commentary on their lives. Archives will be used to attest to the character’s lives. For those who don’t have much archives in terms of photos, audio and visuals, re-enactment will be used to portray their lives. The interviewees will be filmed in their natural environment, with the soft background and focusing on the subject. The past will be compare with the present, e.g KE Masinga presenting during his time and the presenters today at Ukhozi FM. We will use sappier colours when reflecting on the past and bring back the colour when referring to the presence. 

";s:17:"rel_status_update";s:0:"";s:20:"letter_of_motivation";s:0:"";s:14:"representation";s:0:"";s:21:"representation_upload";s:22:"2021/1621028717_1.docx";s:16:"contracts_upload";s:0:"";s:15:"artistic_upload";s:0:"";s:13:"visual_upload";s:0:"";s:12:"project_link";s:0:"";s:16:"project_password";s:0:"";s:8:"synopsis";s:0:"";s:13:"projectBudget";s:6:"587551";s:13:"financialPlan";s:0:"";s:12:"totalSecured";s:1:"0";s:12:"totalApplied";s:6:"587551";s:11:"totalPening";s:1:"0";s:13:"BudgetDeficit";s:6:"587551";s:10:"budgetFile";s:22:"2021/1621030116_1.xlsx";s:9:"proofFile";s:0:"";s:13:"contractProof";s:0:"";s:12:"ackStatement";s:0:"";s:11:"submittedBy";s:15:"Omelga Mthiyane";s:12:"project_role";s:9:"filmmaker";s:10:"filmmanker";s:0:"";s:8:"producer";s:0:"";s:20:"project_co_ordinator";s:0:"";s:13:"project_role2";s:0:"";s:16:"project_category";s:0:"";s:13:"project_brief";s:0:"";s:16:"project_timeline";s:1:"0";s:16:"project_describe";s:0:"";s:12:"organisation";s:0:"";s:20:"explain_organisation";s:0:"";s:15:"briefly_explain";s:0:"";s:14:"socio_economic";s:0:"";s:10:"video_link";s:0:"";s:16:"description_link";s:0:"";s:20:"description_password";s:0:"";s:15:"proposal_upload";s:0:"";s:10:"project_co";s:1:"0";s:8:"complete";s:1:"1";s:6:"status";s:1:"2";s:5:"addon";s:19:"2021-07-02 20:21:03";s:5:"award";s:1:"0";}i:68;O:8:"stdClass":54:{s:2:"id";s:3:"411";s:8:"grant_id";s:2:"18";s:7:"user_id";s:3:"867";s:4:"name";s:9:"Ubungoma ";s:6:"p_date";s:3:"100";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:8:"e_length";s:3:"60+";s:7:"logline";s:50:"A deep dive into the world of African shamanism.
";s:15:"story_structure";s:788:"SYNOPSIS:
Ubungoma is a documentary, which seeks to educate audiences on the practice of Ubungoma, with an added emphasis on the reconnection of Africans to our identity and ancestry. The inspiration of the documentary bore from my own experiences with my former partner's journey as iSangoma/Traditional Healer & my curiosity this subject matter  & how little is known about it particularly in a younger demographic. We aim to explore the relationship between spirituality and modernization, religion & demonstrating how the world co-exist as opposed to collide. 

GENRE:
Participatory Documentary

TARGET MARKET:
This subject matter has such a wide range of appeal across a broad spectrum of LSM’s and ages groups starting from the young and in school right up to the elderly
";s:22:"characters_description";s:231:"We introduce the following interviewees: Gogo Esme, Gogo Malepena, Gogo Muhlavasi Emma Kejoe & Gobelas’ from Mpande’s representing ama Ndau and Mnguni who detail their journeys as well as taking through their various practices.";s:17:"artistic_approach";s:1970:"LOGLINE:
A deep dive into the world of African shamanism.

ACT 1 – UBUNGOMA
The first act serves as the foundation of our subject matter, Ubungoma. We want to evoke emotion from the viewer straight out the gate. The establishing shot of the Sangoma dancing in this scenic view. Focusing not just on the movements but the emotion of the dancer this will be highlighted by using close up shots tightly cropped right alongside wide angles of the sunrise, which will set the scene

ACT 2:   THONGO LAM
This part focuses on educating the viewer on various types of spirits and the way they manifest themselves within their host. Showing the various distinctions and their importance showing how multifaceted it is 

ACT 3:  INKATHAZO
Here we begin to explore the legal ramifications associated with Ubungoma. We dive straight into our first interviewee, the esteemed Makhosi Dhlamini. We want to keep this footage as raw and unrehearsed as possible. Many handheld shots following her around her practice just to give it an intimate feel. Our interviews will be shot with two cameras, our main establishing shot and our second cam focusing on cutaways and secondary shots (tightly zoomed into our subject’s faces to give their stories more raw emotion). We want to keep the backdrop as clean as possible to ensure minimal distractions from the points discussed in the interviews

ACT 4:  HEEDING THE CALL
Inthwaso (initiation) is the very reason that this concept for the film came to be. Our DP, Dino Benedetti’s cinematic eye giving an interesting take on shots of Thwasa’s (initiates) going in to initiation. Depictions of various ceremonies and tying them all together to form a view from the Thwasa’s perspective. We introduce the following interviewees: Gogo Esme, Gogo Malepena, Gogo Muhlavasi Emma Kejoe & Gobelas’ from Mpande’s representing ama Ndau and Mnguni who detail their journeys as well as taking through their various practices

