l called "A Plastic Ocean", their view of the world, the ocean and the anti-plastic campaigns changed.

They start to wonder about their life and their choices. They start recycling even more and using less plastic - they even almost turn Vegan. But as they ponder about this new information and as they speak to others about what they know regarding the ocean and plastic in it, the filmmaker realises that
something they hold very dear to their identity also poses a plastic threat - their hair.

The filmmaker is a hair enthusiast and hair lover, having made previous films about hair and forever finding ways to incorporate hair in any project they do. They also love changing their hair frequently using extra hair to create colourful braids and having braided hairstyles in various colours. The realisation of this conflict causes them to re-think their anti-plastic position - does this mean there will be no more braids? But her grandmother had braids and so did her great, grandmother for sure. Braids are
part of her cultural identity... how does she resolve this issue?

Through their search into the history of African braided hairstyles and frank conversations with other African women who have a close relation with their hair, the filmmaker seeks to finds the general awareness and care amongst other African women regarding issues of hair and identity and the world
and conservation.

But the habit and tradition of braiding is too hard to abandon.

